<TEXT>
terri freeborn tried to spread the word 
she didnt want to be mayor anymore but folks didnt listen 
she won by four votes 
only 45 of the towns 127 registered voters cast ballots 
tuesday 24 of them for mrs freeborn and 20 for richard g bird a 
fourterm town council member and haymarkets vice mayor one 
person did not vote in the mayoral contest 
mrs freeborn 38 had decided for personal reasons several 
weeks ago she did not want to be mayor again of this town of under 
500 it was too late to take her name off the ballot so she tried 
to spread the word she was out of the race 
mrs freeborn a former interior design specialist who has been 
mayor since january 1989 said she will take it one step at a 
time and serve as long as she is able to balance her family and 
official obligations 
i think shes done a very good job to this point and will 
continue to do so said james t shepard one of two new people 
elected to the council 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
this is one community thats happy a 
prison is coming to town 
fayette county will hold a parade here saturday to celebrate 
construction of a 462 million 926inmate mediumsecurity prison 
in nearby mt olive 
the communities in our region have been devastated by setbacks 
in the coal industry and we believe that this correctional 
facility will provide the first step toward economic recovery 
said parade chairman robert jackson 
on hand will be gov gaston caperton and officials from nearby 
counties which also expect to reap economic benefits from the 
prison 
the prison will replace the aging west virginia penitentiary in 
moundsville which has been ordered closed by the state supreme 
court by 1992 
