<TEXT>
after barely six weeks on the job kennedy 
center chairman james d wolfensohn is clear about his goals give 
the marble cultural palace a 30 million facelift fill its stages 
with arts festivals and lay the welcome mat for innercity 
audiences 
im not worried about competition he says im worried 
about my capacity to deliver 
wolfensohn 56 has become a frequent flier aboard the shuttle 
between washington and new york where he also is chairman of 
carnegie hall and president of a highpowered investment banking 
firm since he took command of the kennedy center last month 
without pay 
it didnt take wolfensohn long to discover that the kennedy 
center is an institution in trouble he found a deepening financial 
crisis generally listless programming with a few bright spots 
and nagging confusion over the centers proper artistic role and 
future direction 
when he took the job wolfensohn warned the centers trustees 
that he could spare only two days a week in washington actually 
the time has stretched to three or four days including weekends 
im working very hard he said in an interview but i 
think now is the time to do it by the end of the summer i want to 
have my arms around the problems i dont think i will have solved 
them but i think i will understand them 
the most urgent problem was spotted during wolfensohns 
preliminary examination of the kennedy centers balance sheets 
which showed a cumulative debt of more than 15 million and the 
desperate need for 30 million in longdelayed renovation and 
repairs 
wolfensohn said he won a commitment from white house chief of 
staff john h sununu and the centers congressional trustees to 
find 45 million in federal funds to pay off the debt and refurbish 
the 18yearold national center for the performing arts 
wolfensohn agreed to shoulder responsibility for tapping private 
contributors for the 12 million to 15 million required to finance 
current levels of programming after revenues from ticket sales 
rentals and other sources expanded programming may drive costs to 
20 million to 25 million he estimated 
excitement unfortunately comes very expensive today he 
said and to make this place exciting were going to need a lot 
of money 
wolfensohn said quality programming is the key to attracting 
private support and turning the kennedy center around although 
built by the government the center receives no direct federal 
support for the shows it presents 
wolfensohn wants to build on such innovative but 
littlerecognized kennedy center programs as the annual american 
college theater festival and its imagination celebration arts 
festival for children 
he is starting big he has announced plans for a texas festival 
in june 1991 the first of a series intended to showcase the best 
of performing artists from different states the same year hed 
like to mount a festival featuring artists from the newly emerging 
democracies of eastern europe 
in 1992 hes planning a festival of the americas with 
performances by artists from italy spain and north and south 
america including native americans to mark the 500th anniversary 
of columbus discovery of the new world 
wolfensohn who grew up in a poor family in sydney australia 
has a personal interest in overcoming the kennedy centers 
reputation among local minority residents as an elitist haven for 
the wealthy 
you may think im naive but nourishment of the spirit is not 
a class or financial matter he said i grew up with not a lot 
of money and i used to go to free concerts in sydney it enriched 
my life enormously 
wolfensohn is mulling a plan to bus 30 or 40 poor families from 
innercity neighborhoods to the kennedy center every week to 
introduce them to the performing arts at little or no cost 
to bring a child here who then goes home and gets no 
reinforcement has been a substantial waste of the experience he 
said very often its the parent whos never been here that you 
make your first and biggest hit with 
his goal is to make them feel they can come here and enjoy an 
evening being taken out of themselves into a new world into a 
world of ideas or dreams if we can give them that even for a few 
hours it can make a difference in their lives 
</TEXT>
