<TEXT>
maine voters will reelect a governor in 
november the question is which one 
the choice is between republican gov john r mckernan and his 
democratic predecessor rep joseph e brennan brennan has filled 
mckernans former seat in congress since the two exchanged jobs in 
the 1986 election 
the campaign is decidedly issueoriented the economic slump 
that has gripped the northeast environmental pollution and labor 
relations all loom large but style may prove as decisive as 
substance in the outcome of a race many regard as a tossup so far 
mckernan who at 41 is brennans junior by 14 years is the 
consummate contemporary politician with boyish good looks a 
relaxed public speaking manner and a penchant for staging events 
tailored for the evening news since february 1989 he has been 
married to maines other member of the us house republican rep 
olympia j snowe 
brennan comes across as credible and selfconfident and he 
commands a loyal following that has intensified since he announced 
in late december that he would take on mckernan but he is more 
reserved almost shy at times and has never seemed entirely 
comfortable before tv cameras or large audiences 
running the state government is a lot more than style and 
glitz and photo opportunities and public relations brennan 
observed sizing up his opposition 
lackluster is a word mckernan uses to sum up his challenger 
his administration really didnt have a lot of vision and not a 
lot of energy not a lot of creative ideas to try to prepare for 
the future 
brennan was forced out of the governorship by a provision in the 
state constitution that bars a chief executive who has served two 
consecutive fouryear terms from succeeding himself an obstacle 
that was eliminated by his hiatus in congress 
his decision to give up his seat in southern maines 1st 
congressional district has opened new opportunities for numerous 
other players in a political variation of musical chairs 
among the five democrats competing for the house nomination are 
state attorney general james e tierney the partys nominee in the 
fourway gubernatorial runoff that mckernan won in 1986 and former 
state housing chief elizabeth h mitchell who unsuccessfully 
challenged republican sen william s cohen in 1984 the twoway 
republican race includes david f emery who held the 1st district 
seat for eight years prior to mckernans arrival 
in the gubernatorial race brennan has taken the early lead in 
fundraising in campaign finance reports filed tuesday he claimed 
354000 in contributions and more than 285000 cash on hand 
through april 24 
mckernan who had 148000 available out of contributions 
totaling 273000 said he put off intensive fundraising until 
after the legislative session that ended last month 
brennan said mckernans inferior showing reflects a loss of 
confidence in his performance as governor 
each candidate has said he hopes to raise more than 1 million 
by the general election on nov 6 neither faces opposition in the 
june 12 primary 
mckernan became the first to take his message to the airwaves 
this week running a tv campaign commercial touting his skills at 
managing state government in adverse times a second ad was to air 
during the weekend 
a prime focus of the commercials and of the campaign is 
mckernans response to what was once a projected state budget 
shortfall of 210 million through mid1991 so far three of 
mckernans new england counterparts the governors of vermont 
massachusetts and connecticut have announced amid similar fiscal 
problems that they would not seek reelection 
mckernans budgetbalancing solution was approved by the 
democraticdominated legislature with little tampering 
weve managed this regional problem better than any other 
state in the same boat and we did so without raising taxes like so 
many others mckernan said 
but brennan has hammered away at the issue questioning why the 
administration did not recognize the seriousness of the problem 
sooner he also charges that the steps taken to balance the budget 
ultimately will force increases in municipal property taxes 
mckernan has challenged brennan to offer better alternatives and 
portrays his opponent as a congressman who is at the top of the 
charts in ratings by the special interests and has supported 
all sorts of new federal spending 
the message well be able to send thanks to his record is 
that he was a lackluster leader for the state a big spender and 
that my reelection is critical to keeping maine moving forward 
mckernan said 
</TEXT>
