<TEXT>
two leaders of a leftist revolutionary group 
have been convicted and sentenced to 22 years in prison for 
ordering the assassination of milans police chief more than a 
decade ago 
the 1972 murder of police chief luigi calabresi one of the 
longest unsolved cases of political terrorism in italy marked the 
start of more than a decade of leftist and rightwing terrorism in 
italy 
leftists considered calabresi responsible for the death of an 
anarchist who died after falling from the fourth floor window of a 
police station where he was undergoing interrogation 
wednesdays convictions of adriano sofri and giorgio 
pietrostefani followed the testimony of one of the assassins 
leonardo marino 
marino said he and ovidio bompressi shot calabresi outside the 
police chiefs home on orders of sofri and pietrostefani the 
leaders of lotta continua continuous struggle an extremist group 
committed to proletarian revolution 
after abandoning the leftist struggle pietrostefani became a 
successful business manager while sofri the groups founder 
taught at the florence fine arts academy 
defense lawyers maintainted that the two had nothing to do with 
the murder and that marino was falsely accusing them 
sofri and pietrostefani recieved 22 years as did bompressi 
marino was convicted in the assassination and sentenced to an 
11year term 
