<DOCNO> AP900503-0021 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
small land animals including the 
ferocious 6ounce mutant ninja chipmunk thrived while an 
environmental crisis killed off most giant dinosaurs more than 100 
million years ago a researcher found 
dr robert bakker a university of colorado paleontologist said 
fossils recently unearthed from a 130millionyearold deposit in a 
rock quarry in wyoming showed small dinosaurs mammals turtles and 
other animals flourished in the early cretaceous period a few 
million years after the giant dinosaurs that lived in the jurassic 
period became extinct 
the new fossils are the remains of animals that lived in a 
crisis interval during the early cretaceous period and this is the 
first rock layer that seems to record just what happened and why 
bakker said wednesday 
his preliminary findings were published april 15 in the 
proceedings of the fourth north american paleontological congress 
with several colleagues bakker who first identified the fossil 
beds in the 1970s unearthed a wide array of fossil miniatures 
from the 10 to 12foot thick deposit known as breakfast bench 
near the town of rock river 
the specimens date to the earliest part of the cretaceous 
period a transitional period following the demise of longnecked 
giant dinosaurs such as brontosaurus supersaurus and diplodocus 
bakker said the deposit provides evidence of a classic case of 
david and goliath a variety of diminutive creatures 
overshadowed the great dinosaurs for a time 
after the dinosaurs evolved into a new line of giants again 
eclipsing small animals the same scenario apparently was played 
out about 65 million years later at the end of the cretaceous 
period when another catastrophe of some kind killed off all 
dinosaurs 
new species unearthed at the site include a 20pound herbivorous 
dinosaur a pair of fierce rodentlike mammals weighing less than a 
pound each and a neurologically sophisticated turtle bakker said 
numerous crocodilian remains also were found he said 
the sudden appearance of zofiabaatar a 6ounce furry meateater 
that bakker nicknamed the mutant ninja chipmunk illustrates 
small mammals were taking evolutionary advantage of the swampy 
environment during the crisis he said 
scientists have long been puzzled by the mass extinctions at the 
end of the jurassic period and theories focus on such factors as 
movements of the earth starvation parasites poisons changes in 
climate and meteorites 
but according to bakker dinosaurs became extinct because of 
worldwide diseases that turned into an epidemiological 
nightmare 
dinosaurs didnt go out with a bang they went out with 
worldwide diarrhea he said 
big animals travel and are extremely vulnerable to disease 
bakker said as land bridges formed throughout the globe the 
animals spread hundreds of diseases throughout all continents 
eventually killing the lot 
if youre a species one of the most dangerous things you can 
do is to invade a continent or have a foreign species move in he 
said so the stayathomes have an automatic immunity to this 
tourist trap of exotic disease 
the newly identified creatures apparently thrived in the swampy 
fernchoked environment that marked the end of the jurassic and the 
beginning of the cretaceous periods bakker said 
since fernchoked swamps also were present at the end of the 
cretaceous and during times of other mass dieoffs they may help 
explain why dinosaurs and other large land animals suffered 
repeated extinctions 
scientists studying mass extinction are like criminologists 
tracking a serial killer the clues that finally catch the killer 
usually come from the repeated pattern in the way the crimes were 
committed bakker said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

