<TEXT>
a federal appeals court reversed a judge and 
upheld the states death penalty law opening the way for illinois 
first execution in 28 years 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals in a 30 decision on 
wednesday overturned a ruling last year that the 1977 capital 
punishment law gives prosecutors too much leeway in whether to seek 
the death penalty 
the ruling came in the case of charles silagy convicted of the 
1980 murders of his girlfriend and another woman he is one of 124 
inmates on death row in illinois no one has been executed in the 
state since 1962 
on monday the us supreme court cleared the way for the 
execution of charles walker by ruling that five people who 
challenged his death sentence without his support had no standing 
in the case 
walker condemned in 1983 after pleading guilty to killing two 
people is closest to being executed of the states deathrow 
inmates walker has said he wants to die and has abandoned all 
appeals 
no execution date has been set but corrections officials said 
it could come within 60 to 90 days silagys execution could come 
this year as well said attorney general neil hartigan 
hartigan called the silagy ruling a very substantial victory 
for the people of illinois 
jay miller executive director of the illinois chapter of the 
american civil liberties union said his organization was unhappy 
with both rulings 
we believe its past the time when the united states should 
have a death penalty miller said were left with the soviet 
union and south africa among western nations having the death 
penalty 
wednesdays ruling reversed the decision of us district judge 
harold baker who found the death penalty law unconstitutional 
under the law illinois prosecutors can wait until after a 
conviction to say whether they will seek the death penalty 
silagys lawyers had argued their handling of the case was hampered 
by not knowing what prosecutors would do 
but the appeals court rejected bakers contention that illinois 
law allowed prosecutors to be arbitrary and capricious or 
hindered defense attorneys 
in fact the court said illinois law may even enhance the 
quality of prosecutorial decisions by permitting the prosecutor 
to weigh all of the evidence in his assessment of the 
propriety of seeking the death penalty 
