<TEXT>
the first parkinsons disease patient in the 
united states to be treated with transplanted brain tissue from an 
aborted fetus said the operation has made it easier for him to talk 
and move about 
and a researcher who wrote a paper on the case said wednesday 
the transplant could benefit many parkinsons sufferers 
the bush administration has banned use of federal funds for 
medical research involving fetal tissue which abortion opponents 
say creates an incentive for abortion don nelsons operation was 
paid for privately 
im walking better i dont use crutches or a cane any more 
when im walking in the house nelson 53 said in a telephone 
interview from the denver area my speech has improved the 
volume of my voice is better 
nelson said he probably has 30 percent to 35 percent more 
ability to move than before the operation 1 years ago but he 
still has spells of freezing when he is virtually unable to 
walk 
im hoping that ill continue to get better he said 
nelson also has regained normal functioning of his hands said 
dr curt r freed professor of medicine and pharmacology at the 
university of colorado health sciences center 
the november 1988 operation was the first on a parkinsons 
victim in the united states according to freeds report in the may 
issue of archives of neurology a publication of the american 
medical association 
i think its very exciting to be able to take a chronic 
disease of the nervous system and reverse aspects of it 
freed said in a telephone interview 
parkinsons disease afflicting an estimated 500000 americans 
develops when areas of the brain degenerate and stop producing 
dopamine a brain chemical essential for normal muscle movements 
experiments with rats and monkeys have shown that fetal cells 
transplanted into adult brains can grow and produce dopamine 
about 40 operations on humans have been performed worldwide 
including some others in the united states since nelsons freed 
said 
a patient in sweden improved markedly five months after an 
operation there according to the february issue of science 
magazine 
in nelsons operation tissue from the part of the brain that 
produces dopamine was transplanted from a 7weekold aborted fetus 
into the right side of nelsons brain a needle was used to make 10 
tiny injections with the total fetal material amounting to about 
a sixth of a drop freed said 
eugene redmond jr a yale school of medicine psychiatry 
professor has said that fetal cell implant therapy could become 
the best hope for many people but he has cautioned that a 
study of a single patient cannot yield final conclusions 
