a drug company plans to seek approval to sell an 
experimental new medicine for alzheimers disease even though a 
canadian study released today suggests it does not work 
tetrahydrominoacridine or tha is intended to ease the symptoms 
of alzheimers disease the leading cause of senility among older 
americans 
comparison studies conducted on 39 patients fail to 
demonstrate a significant clinical benefit of tha even though 
some victims appeared initially to improve the canadian 
researchers concluded 
however at warnerlambert the pharmaceutical company that 
makes tha a spokesman said the research should have been limited 
to the minority of alzheimers patients who show an initial 
response to the medicine 
the study directed by dr serge gauthier of mcgill university 
in montreal was published in todays new england journal of 
medicine 
initially the doctors gave increasing doses to see how much of 
the medicine people could tolerate during this phase of the 
research some patients appeared to get somewhat better family 
members said their speech improved and they were able to do such 
simple tasks as answer the telephone or set the table 
during the next part of the research patients were randomly 
assigned to take tha or dummy placebos this time the apparent 
benefits did not return and there was no important difference 
between the two groups according to the study 
the researchers speculated that patients might have built up a 
resistance to the drug or that family members might have imagined 
the seeming early improvement 
at warnerlambert spokesman barry cohen said the company 
believes the drug is useful and plans to ask the us food and drug 
administration in june for permission to sell it under the brand 
name cognex 
the company estimates about 40 percent of alzheimers patients 
could benefit from the drug he said though it is not a cure 
cohen said the companys own study being conducted at us 
hospitals is encouraging but he did not disclose details of the 
findings 
