<TEXT>
patriarch pimen the head of the russian orthodox 
church who presided over the faiths reawakening after decades of 
repression died today at the age of 79 tass reported 
no cause of death was given in the terse announcement in recent 
years pimen rarely celebrated services because of his increasing 
frailty 
pimen as patriarch of moscow and all russia led tens of 
millions of believers in the officially atheist soviet union 
after a historic meeting with president mikhail s gorbachev in 
1988 the year the church celebrated the 1000th anniversary of 
its founding in russia pimen praised the soviet leaders reform 
efforts toward religion 
under pimens leadership the russian orthodox church supported 
official soviet policies especially the leaderships 
pronouncements on peace and nuclear disarmament 
the church carefully remained in the sphere that was left for 
it the spiritual development of individual believers 
recently however its leaders have cautiously criticized the 
laws that restrict church activities 
for centuries russian orthodox church leaders managed close and 
sometimes difficult relations with the government but the close 
contact that pimen and other top church officials have maintained 
with the communist party angered some activists who called it 
collaboration 
born sergei izvekov in moscow he entered the monastery in 
october 1927 and took the religious name pimen he continued his 
religious education at a time when authorities violently repressed 
the church and became a priest in 1931 
until 1946 he was a priest in a cathedral in murom a city 140 
miles east of moscow 
pimen moved rapidly to posts in odessa rostovondon and pskov 
being handed more and more responsibility 
in 1960 he became a member of the churchs holy synod and 
three years later was named metropolitan of krutitsky and 
kolomenskoye 
he was chosen church leader in 1971 
in the era of gorbachevs social and political reforms pimen 
even was elected to the soviet parliament in march 1989 
he was a member of the world peace committee and traveled 
extensively in 1982 he addressed a un disarmament conference in 
new york and in 1986 he issued a message titled on war and peace 
in the nuclear age 
he was awarded the officially sponsored soviet peace committees 
gold medal and the governments order of the peoples friendship 
a memorial service was planned for friday at bogoyavlensky 
cathedral i moscow no funeral plans were announced 
