with sens george mitchell dmaine the majority leader bob dole 
rkan the minority leader house speaker thomas s foley and rep 
robert michel rill the house minority leader 
on capitol hill both liberal and conservative lawmakers are 
likely to challenge the senate budget committees decision to slash 
defense spending next year by 99 billion below the level bush 
wants 
the budget panel on wednesday adopted a democraticwritten 12 
trillion spending plan that sets defense spending at 2939 billion 
in fiscal 1991 which begins oct 1 in a year that has seen 
congressional democrats trying to reduce pentagon coffers that 
would be the deepest cut yet in bushs defense plans 
sen charles grassley of iowa was the only republican to join 
the panels majority democrats in the 149 vote for final passage 
democrats touted the plan which claims to shrink the deficit by 
43 billion as a response to the cold war thaw 
this is a clear shift in priorities a shift away from massive 
spending on defense and a greater concentration on the domestic 
needs of this country said committee chairman james sasser 
dtenn 
i dont believe its anywhere close to being right or prudent 
nor will it permit a proper builddown of our defenses countered 
