<TEXT>
african national congress leaders 
began a second day of talks with the government today and 
officials said both sides were committed to finding a way to bring 
blacks into the political process 
the whiteled government and the anc the countrys most 
powerful opposition group are seeking to clear the way for future 
negotiations on a constitution that would give the black majority 
the vote 
this first round of talks which opened wednesday are the first 
ever between the government and anc they are to end friday 
when all of us departed wednesdays talks the general 
feeling was that not only is movement forward necessary but that 
it is possible said thabo mbeki the head of the ancs foreign 
affairs department 
we had people sitting in that room who are perfectly 
reasonable and we are all committed to finding a solution mbeki 
told more than 200 people at the cape town press club 
anc spokesman patrick terror lekota wrote in an article 
published today in several newspapers black south africans have 
done every possible thing under the sun to get whites to negotiate 
a democratic constitution now it seems clear that we shall 
negotiate that kind of constitution in the near future 
following wednesdays talks the two sides issued a joint 
statement saying the discussions were characterized by openness 
and straightforwardness 
before opening the talks president fw de klerk and anc leader 
nelson mandela stood side by side and called for the swift 
abolition of apartheid 
in a bid to calm white fears about a black government mandela 
gave part of his statement in afrikaans the language of the 
dutchdescended afrikaners who make up 3 million of the countrys 5 
million whites and dominate the government 
de klerk said south africans of all races wanted rapid change 
all political parties must work together to find a peaceful 
solution to the countrys racial and political divisions he said 
under the apartheid system of racial segregation the countrys 
28 million blacks have no voice in national affairs while the 
whites control the government and the economy 
the anc says that before constitutional negotiations can begin 
the government must lift the state of emergency allow exiled 
activists to return and release activists convicted of politically 
motivated crimes 
the government wants the anc to renounce its largely ineffective 
armed struggle 
all these matters are on the agenda the two parties said 
the government has said that constitutional negotiations will 
include several opposition groups in addition to the anc 
however rightwing whites and radical black groups oppose any 
negotiated powersharing agreement between whites and blacks 
the proapartheid conservative party marched out of a debate in 
parliament on wednesday to protest the talks between the government 
and the anc the leader of the conservatives andries treurnicht 
said the government had no right to negotiate with an organization 
that has carried out guerrilla attacks and still was committed to 
an armed struggle 
meanwhile the militant pan africanist congress has accused the 
anc of appeasement for agreeing to meet with the government 
the pan africanists say the only matter they will negotiate is the 
direct transfer of power from whites to blacks 
de klerk has promised to end white rule but opposes a 
oneperson onevote system he says such a system would replace 
white domination with black domination 
the anc says it is committed to a full democratic system with no 
special rights for minorities the anc also wants a radical 
restructuring of the economy that could include government control 
of banks gold mines and other leading industries 
the talks are the first between a white government and an anc 
delegation since the organization was founded in 1912 the 
discussions are being held at the groote schuur estate once the 
official home of south african presidents 
