<TEXT>
latvias legislature opened a session 
today to begin discussing whether to join baltic neighbors 
lithuania and estonia in asserting its independence from moscow 
lithuanian president vytautas landsbergis attended the opening 
session to be with my brothers and pro and antiindependence 
protesters stood aside as the deputies entered the parliament 
building 
about 50 soviet army officers who live in latvia gathered with 
signs proclaiming the people and the army are united and we 
wont go the way of lithuania 
a few steps away proindependence protesters carried banners 
saying the soviet army must go home and independence for 
latvia protesters carried soviet flags or the redandwhite 
latvian flag 
the legislature or supreme soviet discussed procedural 
questions and a vote on independence was likely friday deputies 
from the proindependence peoples front said they believe they can 
muster the needed twothirds majority 
the soviet news agency tass said the peoples front and its 
supporters had 131 of 201 seats in the legislature a twothirds 
majority would require 135 votes and peoples front activists 
believe they can find the extra votes 
anatoly gorbunov latvias president backed independence in a 
speech after being nominated to a new term 
i believe that the renewal of a legally sovereign nation must 
be accomplished he said declaring it a normal way of life for 
all the residents of latvia gorbunov was expected to win 
election to continue as president 
but he said the republic could not expect help from the west 
the world on account of 5 million baltic people is not going to 
risk what has been done in the area of arms control and by mikhail 
gorbachev he said 
landsbergis told latvian radio in an interview i see and feel 
that latvia wont retreat from the principle of independence 
he told the latvian deputies to be strong and have courage 
in his own republic officials of landsbergis government said 
today that shortages were beginning to touch medical supplies 
lithuania declared independence from the soviet union on march 
11 in response the kremlin imposed harsh economic sanctions 
including a sharp reduction in oil and gas supplies about two 
weeks ago 
the republic of 38 million people has been struggling 
economically ever since the embargo was imposed with plant 
closings forcing thousands to stop work and food and fuel being 
rationed 
a similar independence measue was adopted march 30 by estonia 
which with fellow baltic states latvia and lithuania was forcibly 
annexed by the soviet union in 1940 
the measure being debated in latvia would unlike lithuanias 
declaration take effect only after an indefinite transition period 
lawmakers also were expected to vote on dropping the soviet 
socialist from latvias name leaving it simply the republic of 
latvia 
deputies belonging to the latvian peoples front 
proindependence movement said they agreed to the goslow plan on 
secession after watching lithuania struggle unsuccessfully to 
persuade moscow to begin negotiations 
we didnt slam the door and then start to knock said romans 
apsitis a law professor were leaving the door open and still 
moving toward independence 
the proposal would leave most of the republics sovietera 
constitution intact but it would also assert latvias claim to 
independence and its right to reestablish its traditional 
parliament 
although the latvian measure would be less drastic than 
lithuanias it also would not be within the secession procedure 
outlined in a soviet law passed in march 
the law obliges any republic seeking independence to gain 
approval through a referendum and wait up to five years while 
negotiating terms of divorce with moscow opponents say the law 
effectively prevents any republic from seceding 
apsitis said that at most latvia would consider a role in a 
reconfigured soviet confederation but only after gaining 
independence 
because of latvias delicate ethnic balance a declaration of 
independence would likely be less radical than lithuanias 
declaration 
in contrast to lithuania where 80 percent of the people are 
ethnic lithuanian only about 54 percent of latvias population of 
27 million people is ethnic latvian most of the rest are ethnic 
russians many of whom oppose independence 
it will pit russians and latvians against each other said 
soviet army major alexander skryachev 
in the past year latvia has copied lithuanias daring political 
moves in december it abolished the communist partys guarantee on 
power in february it condemned the 1940 act that formalized its 
annexation by the soviet union and last month a large segment of 
its communist party broke off from its moscowbased parent party 
all the moves came within months sometimes weeks of similar 
lithuanian actions 
