<TEXT>
the boy scouts of america organization has asked 
a federal judge to dismiss a lawsuit filed by an agnostic who said 
he and his 6yearold son were rejected from a scout chapter for 
refusing to profess faith in god 
elliott welsh of suburban hinsdale filed the lawsuit last fall 
saying the organization practiced religious discrimination 
the boy scouts based in irving texas has required its 
members now numbering about 43 million to do my duty to god 
and my country since its founding 80 years ago said scouts 
spokesman lee sneath 
walsh and his son mark now 7 were rejected when they noted on 
cub scout membership applications they would not agree to religious 
stipulations because they were agnostic the cub scouts is a branch 
of the boy scouts for younger boys 
when the scouts refused to change the policy walsh filed suit 
charging that it violated the part of the 1964 civil rights act 
that bans religious discrimination in public accommodations 
the scouts contend their units are more like private clubs 
which are excluded from that provision of the civil rights law 
scouts attorney thomas d allen asked us district judge ilana 
rovner on wednesday to dismiss the lawsuit 
rovner delayed the request for further consideration after 
welshs attorney richard grossman said the scouts are a public 
body because they invite all boys to join 
if theyre going to give a flier to every kid in the 1st grade 
inviting him to join then theyve got to accept the consequences 
of having their organization subject to the same laws as a 
mcdonalds or a movie theater grossman argued 
also wednesday robert l sherman national spokesman for 
american atheists inc held a news conference to demand that the 
united way cut off its annual support to the boy scouts in the 
chicago area after his 8yearold son was rejected from the club 
for the same reason 
he said the united way should cut off about 15 million to 
chicago chapters of the boy scouts because of the united way 
policy prohibiting gifts to organizations that discriminate on the 
basis of religion the united way will appoint a committee to look 
into the charges said spokeswoman julia hess 
sneath said the scouts will not change the policy even if the 
united way organizations cut off their donations which make up 
about 13 percent of the organizations 350 million annual 
operating budget 
as a private membership organization we have a right to set 
our own standards for membership and leadership he said we do 
not discriminate on the basis of religion and i dont know that 
anyone has ever proved that having no belief is a religion 
