a labor activist set himself on fire 
and leaped to his death from an auto parts plant thursday becoming 
the first fatality in the wave of labor unrest that has swept 
across south korea in the past week 
the government issued a new warning against violent labor 
protests which have paralyzed vital export industries prime 
minister kang younghoon said south koreas slumping economy was at 
stake 
the government is facing the worst crisis since the 
inauguration of president roh taewoo in 1988 kang said rohs 
inauguration followed months of violent protests against his 
authoritarian predecessor 
government officials are alarmed by mounting public discontent 
with the roh administration whose popularity hit an alltime low 
of 12 percent in a recent public poll conducted by the ruling 
democratic liberal party 
kim youngil 28 doused himself with paint thinner set it 
ablaze and jumped from the roof of a twostory building at his 
plant in the southern industrial town of changwon 
kim a union activist at the tongil industry co died of burns 
and head injuries at a hospital two hours later 
news reports said kim left two letters complaining of a hard 
life and protesting alleged police surveillance of his labor 
activity 
why is my life so hard mother reports quoted kim as saying 
in a letter addressed to his family 
