<TEXT>
the national assembly today approved a bill that 
would bar anyone who provokes racial hatred or violence from 
holding elected office and government jobs for five years 
the legislation aimed at the extremeright national front 
party was passed by the assembly 307265 after an allnight debate 
and now goes to the senate where it can be revised before being 
returned to the lower house 
it must be signed by president francois mitterand to become law 
jeanmarie le pen the leader of the national front said the 
bill was without precedence in a western democracy le pen 
watched from the public gallery as the sole national front deputy 
struggled without success to introduce 80 amendments to block or 
water down the measure 
an alliance between the socialist and communist parties which 
control a majority of seats in the assembly pushed the bill 
through while most of the conservative opposition voted against it 
the bill bans those found guilty by a court of racial 
discrimination or inciting racial hatred or violence from running 
for office holding a government post or sitting on a jury for five 
years 
the bill also makes it a misdemeanor to deny the existence of 
crimes against humanity committed by the nazis during world war ii 
le pen won global notoriety in 1987 by terming the deaths of 6 
million jews in the world war ii death camps a detail of 
history 
because we are all democrats le pen has never been denied his 
freedom of expression prime minister michel rocard said before 
opening the debate but for the same reason we cant accept that 
he can hold out these racist and antisemitic proposals without 
penalty 
the proposal also requires that magazines newspapers and 
broadcasting outlets provide rightofreply space to victims of 
racially defamatory stories 
conservative deputies argued that the measure unnecessarily 
tampered with an 1881 law guaranteeing freedom of the press and 
accused the communists of opportunism 
at a news conference before the debate le pen said the law 
violated democratic traditions 
the french parliament is being called on to institute a new 
penalty the civil and political death of citizens guilty of 
opposing immigration and defending the french identity he said 
the bills approval comes after a government commission in march 
said that racism particularly against north african immigrants is 
spreading in france 
le pen a former paratrooper founded the national front in 
1972 it has built its following by opposing immigration the 
countrys most explosive social issue le pen advocates expelling 
the 34 million moslem immigrants living in france 
the fronts support is strongest among white voters in areas 
where there are large numbers of north african and black immigrants 
the party once held 35 seats in the assembly and captured 14 
percent of the vote in the 1988 presidential elections it lost 
most of its seats due to electoral reforms 
</TEXT>
