<TEXT>
optimistic government and african 
national congress leaders said thursday they were making progress 
in clearing the way for fullscale negotiations on ending 
whiteminority rule 
the two sides issued a joint communique after a second day of 
talks and said both leaders expressed satisfaction with the 
progress achieved thus far and would continue tomorrow to work 
toward bridging differences 
the delegations led by president fw de klerk and anc deputy 
president nelson mandela met amid tight security at a suburban 
estate they are the first formal talks between the government and 
anc since the black nationalist group was founded 78 years ago 
the first day of talks wednesday concentrated on a general 
discussion of the issues each side regards as obstacles the 
communique said 
thursdays meeting was devoted to a widerranging discussion 
and penetrating analysis of these specific issues in an attempt to 
identify the differences more clearly in the hope that proposals 
could emerge on how to bridge these differences said the 
communique 
the talks were scheduled to end friday evening but the argus 
newspaper in cape town said they were likely to be continued at a 
later date because agreement probably would not be reached on all 
issues by friday 
the delegations are seeking to remove obstacles to formal 
negotiations on a new constitution that would give the countrys 
black majority a voice in national affairs 
thabo mbeki a senior member of the anc delegation expressed 
optimism when he spoke to reporters during a lunch break thursday 
when all of us departed wednesdays talks the general 
feeling was that not only is movement forward necessary but that 
it is possible said mbeki 
we had people sitting in that room who are perfectly 
reasonable and we are all committed to finding a solution he 
said 
sources of the governing national party who refused to be 
identified said the government also was confident the talks would 
lead to fullscale negotiations on changing the constitution 
as a precondition to those talks the anc is demanding the 
government end a nearly 4yearold state of emergency release all 
political prisoners and allow antigovernment activists to return 
from exile 
the government has countered with demands that the anc renounce 
its armed struggle and help stop a wave of violence that has 
claimed hundreds of lives in recent months 
in an outline of the ancs position carried by newspapers 
thursday anc spokesman patrick lekota stressed that the group 
which was legalized by de klerk in february was making every 
effort to clear the way for constitutional negotiations 
he said the majority of south africans were looking to the talks 
to find a peaceful solution to the countrys racial divisions 
while holding grimly to our views we shall do everything 
short of selling out to help the government remove the obstacles to 
a political settlement he wrote 
both the anc and government have come under fire for the talks 
radical black groups that say only force can end apartheid are 
angry at the anc for talking to the government and white extremist 
groups oppose the government meeting with blacks 
the national party stressed the government was negotiating from 
a position of strength the government party officials said would 
insist on a wide range of guarantees to safeguard the interests of 
the countrys 5 million whites and other minorities 
these guarantees would include a parliamentary chamber where 
whites would have a legislative veto and retention of afrikaans as 
an official language the party officials said 
the anc has demanded a oneperson onevote democratic system 
with no special rights for any racial group it also wants a 
redistribution of wealth to aid millions of impoverished blacks 
