<TEXT>
the veterans affairs department lost as much 
as 392 million in one year by failing to collect from private 
insurance companies for health care according to the general 
accounting office 
the report released this week by the congressional auditing 
agency says the va missed collecting from 55 million to 392 
million in socalled third party reimbursements in 1988 
the department spends about 10 billion a year on health care 
for veterans including those with private insurance congress in 
1986 gave the government the right to collect from private insurers 
as a means of cutting the deficit 
the report did note however collections have greatly exceeded 
the costs of collecting the money in the 1988 fiscal year the 
report said the va spent 8 million to collect about 100 million 
from insurers 
the report said va centers could increase collections 
significantly if they used better methods to identify insured 
veterans and bill insurers and committed more people and time to 
collections 
even when centers identified insured veterans they did not 
always bill insurers the report said citing inadequate controls 
and manual billing systems 
the report said many veterans are confused or afraid that 
disclosures about insurance would jeopardize their admittance to 
the centers 
the veterans department operates 172 hospitals 233 outpatient 
clinics and 119 nursing homes the hospitals recorded 11 million 
admissions and 20 million outpatient visits 
the report was based on collections at six va medical centers 
albany ny bay pines fla martinsburg wva minneapolis 
seattle and west los angeles calif 
the report was requested by sen frank h murkowski rala the 
ranking minority member on the senate veterans affairs committee 
the va in its response acknowledged problems and said it was 
taking a number of steps to address them 
in its 1991 budget proposal the department said it would 
introduce legislation to improve and expand its thirdparty 
collection activities 
