<TEXT>
the 1000 fine for violations of child labor 
laws is failing to deter employers lawmakers said thursday as they 
proposed increasing the federal fine to 10000 
businesses that repeatedly hire children for dangerous jobs or 
work youngsters for too many hours would face fines of up to 
100000 and yearlong jail terms for their executives under the 
measure 
the legislation was introduced in congress along with the 
release of a study that reports such violations jumped 150 percent 
in a recent sixyear period 
under the bill the labor department would have to keep 
nationwide statistics on workplace fatalities injuries and 
illnesses involving workers under age 18 
house members who introduced the measure said the size of the 
nations child labor problem is unknown because of poor 
recordkeeping and detection 
we have grabbed onto the large tail of an unseen beast said 
rep charles schumer dny 
the labor department which has recently cracked down on child 
labor violators is reviewing changes in such laws though the 
agency has not taken a stand on raising the penalty for each 
infraction to 10000 it has made administrative changes to 
increase the fine structure 
previously the labor department fined businesses 1000 for 
each child involved it has now started fining employers 1000 for 
each infraction 
rep don pease dohio another sponsor said the fines are 
often reduced by the labor department and dont even amount to a 
slap on the wrist 
the measure would also impose stiff penalties for willful 
violations that result in a childs death or injury 
if a worker under 18 suffered serious bodily injury from a 
willful violation the employer would face a fine of up to 250000 
and a sevenyear jail term violations involving a death would 
carry the same fine and 14 years in jail 
a general accounting office study said information provided by 
26 states showed that in 1988 children under age 18 suffered more 
than 31500 workrelated injuries and illnesses 
the gao the investigative arm of congress said the huge 
increase in detected child labor violations may be due to a tight 
labor market and increased enforcement by the labor department 
the number of child labor violations uncovered by the labor 
department grew from about 10000 in fiscal year 1983 to nearly 
25000 in fiscal 1989 the study said 
last month the labor department uncovered about 12000 
violations during a threeday nationwide sweep those violations 
are expected to result in fines of nearly 4 million to employers 
