<TEXT>
a piano concerto written 150 years ago by franz 
liszt was being performed thursday night for the first time and 
the soloist says the honor of playing the longlost composition was 
a gift from god 
all i have to say is there are 50 million pianists out there 
right now that would like to be me pianist janina fialkowska 
said hours before the debut of the concerto for piano and orchestra 
before a sellout crowd at the chicago symphony orchestra 
fialkowska acknowledged some nervousness and a tremendous sense 
of responsibility in performing the work discovered by a doctoral 
student from the university of chicago doing archival research in 
europe 
i was much more careful with this said fialkowska a 
canadian who now lives in connecticut i had to approach every 
note of the piece and choose a way that would satisfy myself the 
public and liszt 
i have grown to love the piece she said i want the piece 
to be a success i want the piece to be loved 
its a gift from god she said of being asked to perform the 
concerto 
liszt a hungarian who lived from 1811 until 1886 was a 
virtuoso pianist and a prolific composer who performed and taught 
across europe 
he divided his household in so many cities that he invariably 
lost track of some materials said rena mueller a liszt scholar 
who teaches at new york university also he gave sections away 
as gifts sometimes 
it took the work of an enterprising scholar jay rosenblatt to 
piece together sections of liszts work found in the german cities 
nuremberg and weimar and budapest hungary to form the 
onemovement 15minute piece now called concerto opus posthumous 
the materials had been located before and had been seen by 
other scholars said mueller mr rosenblatt was able to put 
them together into a single coherent piece 
the result she said is a large original composition 
it probably dates to the late 1830s at a point when he was 
touring the cultural world demonstrating just what could be done 
on this relatively young instrument the piano she said 
it is one of the major works of liszt that has been 
discovered since the second world war major in terms of scale and 
in terms of its overall importance to the repertory she said 
rosenblatt who is working on his dissertation at the university 
of chicago said thursday he would be on hand for the world 
premiere of the piece at orchestra hall 
alan walker chairman of the music department at mcmaster 
university in ontario and a liszt scholar said the piece 
demonstrates liszts comfort in orchestrating while he was still in 
his early 20s 
the prevailing wisdom is that he didnt learn to handle the 
orchestra until 10 or 15 years later walker said 
despite the fanfare for thursdays premiere the performance of 
the piece was sure to provoke some controversy walker said 
when we say that it was lost its not strictly true because 
several people including liszt himself always knew where the piece 
was walker said 
but liszt didnt publish it so this raises an ethical 
question as to whether or not a piece that liszt never bothered to 
publish in his lifetime should be published at all 
</TEXT>
