<TEXT>
patriarch pimen who headed the russian orthodox 
church through years of repression and a recent renewal in a more 
tolerant soviet union died thursday at the age of 79 
pimen died at his moscow residence after a long illness the 
official soviet news agency tass said it did not elaborate in 
recent years pimen became increasingly frail and rarely celebrated 
services when he did appear in public he needed help to stand or 
move 
as patriarch of moscow and all russia since 1971 pimen led tens 
of millions of believers in the officially atheist soviet union 
some critics accused him of collaboration because he operated 
within strict limits imposed by the kremlin 
probably the way he will be remembered is as a pious monk 
rather than as a dynamic church leader said jane ellis a 
scholar at keston college center for the study of religion and 
communism based in britain 
after a historic meeting with mikhail s gorbachev in 1988 the 
year christianity celebrated the 1000th anniversary of its 
founding in russia pimen praised the soviet leaders reforms 
affecting religion 
in the early years of pimens leadership the russian orthodox 
church supported official soviet policies especially the 
leaderships pronouncements on peace and nuclear disarmament that 
were critical of the united states 
the state rewarded pimen for his loyalty he was a member of the 
governmentsponsored world peace committee and traveled 
extensively in 1982 he addressed a un disarmament conference in 
new york 
he was awarded the officially sponsored soviet peace committees 
gold medal on his 70th birthday he received the governments 
order of the peoples friendship 
for centuries before the 1917 bolshevik revolution russian 
czars imposed political controls on the church but in the 1920s 
and 1930s the communist party went further razing churches and 
imprisoning and sometimes executing clerics 
that repression eased in recent decades nevertheless top 
church officials felt compelled to maintain close ties with 
communist authorities and that angered some religious activists 
as more and more soviets have been drawn to the faith and 
worshiped openly there have been more challenges for the russian 
orthodox church many activists have questioned whether pimen had 
the strength and the inclination to lead the church into a new era 
ellis said pimen was not a strong advocate for the church 
he was one of those like other leaders of the church who 
really was put in the position where in order to keep any church 
life alive at all had to acquiesce and do what the government 
tells them to do and he was one of those who quite clearly did 
that she said in an interview thursday 
metropolitan pitirim head of the russian orthodox churchs 
printing department and reportedly close to gorbachev and his wife 
raisa is regarded as a possible successor to pimen ellis said 
about a halfdozen bishops could be seen as contenders for the post 
and there was no clear frontrunner 
church officials gathered in moscow on thursday night to elect 
an acting patriarch and resolve other matters concerning pimens 
death tass reported but there was no immediate word on who was 
chosen by tradition the churchs top leadership body known as 
the local council and made up of all metropolitans archbishops 
bishops and representatives of the clergy and laymen will gather 
within six months to elect a permanent successor 
born june 23 1910 into a whitecollar family sergei izvekov 
entered the monastery in october 1927 and took the religious name 
pimen he continued his religious education at a time when 
authorities violently repressed the church and he became a priest 
in 1931 
until 1946 he was a priest in a cathedral in murom a city 
about 140 miles east of moscow 
pimen advanced rapidly into more responsible posts in odessa 
rostovondon and pskov in 1960 he was named archbishop and 
became a member of the holy synod the administrative organ of the 
russian orthodox church three years later he was named 
metropolitan of krutitsky and kolomenskoye 
he was chosen patriarch in 1971 succeeding patriarch alexei 
who had led the church 25 years 
pimen was elected to the soviet parliament in march 1989 
we church people ardently pray for the success of the 
restructuring process perestroika and strive to do everything 
possible for its development tass quoted pimen as saying in 1988 
a memorial service was planned friday at bogoyavlensky cathedral 
in moscow no funeral plans were announced 
</TEXT>
