<TEXT>
highway deaths are virtually certain to rise 
if automakers are forced to significantly improve fuel efficiency 
by the end of the decade the governments top traffic safety 
official said thursday 
injuries will be more severe deaths will increase because 
automakers would be forced to build smaller cars said jerry r 
curry administrator of the national highway traffic safety 
administration 
in a speech to the society of automotive engineers curry 
criticized special interest groups that want to become the high 
priests of gasoline mileage standards which his agency sets 
under current law new fleets all the cars an automaker 
produces in one model year must have an overall average of 275 
miles per gallon that means some models may fall short of the 
minimum if others exceed it for light trucks the minimum is 20 
mpg 
a bill in the senate would require automakers to improve their 
fleet averages 20 percent by the 1995 model year and 40 percent by 
2001 the minimum for the typical fleet would rise to 344 mpg in 
1995 and 402 mpg by 2001 
environmentalists support the bill saying major improvement in 
fuel economy should be the centerpiece of efforts to curb global 
warming but automakers say the measure would wreak havoc in their 
industry and force them to stop making all but the smallest cars 
curry said it seems inevitable that a big increase in the 
standards would drastically reduce car sizes 
he said in an interview his agency was studying the impact 
increased standards would have on highway deaths 
its very clear from the preliminary data that while we cant 
tell you specifically what it is there is a very definite increase 
in the number of deaths as you downsize cars curry said 
theres no question that smaller cars are more dangerous than 
larger cars its a matter of physics 
sen richard bryan dnev sponsor of the fuel economy 
legislation said automakers had issued equally dire warnings in 
the mid1970s when the current 275 mpg standard was proposed 
these are the same people who said catalytic converters could 
never be done who said we couldnt reach the 27 mpg standard who 
fought air bags sideimpact standards their track record on this 
issue has not been impressive bryan said 
highway fatalities have decreased steadily despite reduced car 
weight in the past two decades he said 
curry also supported automakers contention that the proposed 
increase would restrict consumer choice 
forcing products on the public against consumer wishes is what 
the soviets call centralized economic planning curry said mr 
gorbachev says it does not work in russia can we expect it to work 
here 
