angami zapu phizo who fought for independence for 
the northeast indian state of nagaland and was condemned to death 
in absentia has died in exile at age 83 sources at the indian 
high commission said thursday 
he died monday the sources said speaking on condition of 
anonymity the cause of death was not disclosed 
phizo a christian and chief of nagalands angami tribe had 
been in exile since 1960 when he fled indian troops sent to the 
mountainous state on the burmese border 
phizo cooperated with the japanese during world war ii in their 
failed bid to overthrow british colonial rule in india later he 
petitioned indian political and spiritual leader mahatma gandhi to 
support the naga claim for independence but failed to gain gandhis 
support 
after india gained independence from british rule in 1947 
nagaland was made a part of the indian state of assam 
in response phizo founded the naga national council and was 
its president it demanded a separate naga homeland and organized 
armed resistance against indian forces 
the government of independent indias first prime minister 
jawaharal nehru initially held talks with phizo but later it sent 
indian soldiers to nagaland to fight the guerrillas and phizo was 
condemned to death in absentia for murder and declaring war on the 
indian state 
phizo fled to zurich and in 1960 with the help of a church of 
england missionary the rev michael scott came to london 
nagaland is about 160 miles long and 70 miles at its widest 
point its population of 775000 is descended from fierce tribal 
headhunters the british in days of colonial rule sent 18 military 
expeditions from 1832 until 1887 to try to subdue them 
nagaland formerly the naga hills district of assam and the 
former tuensang frontier division of the northeast frontier agency 
was officially inaugurated as a separate state of the indian union 
in 1963 but many nagas remained dissatisfied 
fighting between naga guerrillas and indian forces resumed in 
1972 and still continues the indian government has banned all 
foreigners from visiting nagaland and the other six northeast 
indian states without a special permit 
the sources at the indian high commission said phizos son had 
made inquiries about the possibility of taking his fathers body 
back to nagaland a delegation from nagaland was traveling to 
london to make the arrangements they said 
