<TEXT>
the nation spent nearly 540 billion on health 
in 1988 a 104 percent increase over 1987 the department of 
health and human services said thursday 
the statistics the most recent available show a return to a 
doubledigit growth rate after smaller increases in 1986 and 1987 
said hhs secretary louis sullivan 
health expenditures he said have been growing faster than the 
economy for many years and will strain the ability of americans to 
pay for quality care 
the report by the agencys health care financing administration 
said the dollar amount spent on health care in 1988 was 117 percent 
greater than the sum spent in 1980 
per capita spending increased 100 percent from 1980 to 1988 
among the other statistics in the hhs report 
national health expenditures accounted for 111 percent of the 
gross national product in 1988 up from 91 percent in 1980 
personal health expenditures the lions share of health 
spending increased 10 percent in 1988 
general economic inflation accounted for less than half the 
increase in personal health spending medical price inflation was 
responsible for about a quarter of the increase other factors 
including population changes volume of services and use of 
hightech services accounted for the rest of the increase 
the federal government financed 30 percent of personal health 
spending mainly through its medicare and medicaid programs state 
and local governments contributed another 11 percent private 
health insurance financed 32 percent and patients paid directly 
for 24 percent 
national spending on physician services increased 131 percent 
spending on hospital services was up 93 percent 
of each dollar spent on health care 39 cents went to hospitals 
and 19 cents went to physicians nursing homes received 8 cents per 
dollar 
</TEXT>
