<TEXT>
four marine shows that allow human swimmers to 
frolic with dolphins will be allowed to continue on an experimental 
basis a federal agency announced thursday 
the national oceanic and atmospheric administrations said it 
would allow the swimwiththedolphin program to continue until 
the end of 1991 but only at the four locations where such programs 
now exist 
no new permits however will be issued to other locations at 
this time and no additional dolphins may be captured for use in 
these programs the announcement said 
federal officials said the programs must follow new conditions 
and will be closely monitored 
the announcement said that the national marine fisheries 
service a part of noaa investigated the dolphinswimmer programs 
the agency found no physical evidence that the dolphins involved 
in these programs have suffered more health problems than dolphins 
which are used for public display in aquaria habitats 
three of the dolphin programs are in florida and the fourth is 
in hawaii 
noaa made the ruling after environmental groups expressed 
concern about the health and safety of dolphins in the swim 
programs the marine fisheries service said it received hundreds of 
letters about the dolphinswimmer program during the last six 
months 
officials said the swimwiththedolphin programs will be 
allowed to continue on an experimental basis so more information 
can be obtained on the wellbeing of dolphins participating 
based on this information the programs may be extended beyond 
1991 or discontinued 
the marine fisheries service said it will closely monitor the 
programs to assure that new conditions imposed are followed 
the new conditions include assuring that dolphins are given 
additional rest periods provisions for additional security a 
means for the dolphins to escape from the swimming public and that 
no more than two human swimmers per dolphin will be permitted in 
the water at the same time 
also the new conditions require the training for program staff 
members and forbid any participant to hold pull or grab the 
dolphins 
