<TEXT>
polyester postage stamps will be sold through 
automatic teller machines at banks in a sixmonth test beginning 
may 18 in seattle the postal service announced thursday 
spokesman art shealy said the stamps will be testmarketed in a 
joint venture by the postal service and seafirst bank first at 
about 15 seattle locations and then at other seafirst branches in 
washington state 
shealy said the sheets of stamps were designed to be like 
currency so that they could be dispensed the same way cash is 
dispensed through the machines 
he said the sheets each with a dozen 25cent stamps would cost 
3 apiece debited against the customers bank account 
the stamp is designed to be selfadhesive requiring no licking 
shealy said 
we think it answers quite a large portion of the publics 
request for a more convenient stamp he said it is 
humidityresistant so they dont stick together it is really a 
stamp of the future 
if the seattle test is a success shealy said the stamps will 
be tried out nationwide in the spring of 1991 
the postal service already sells stamps through supermarkets and 
other types of store and shealy said selling them through automatic 
teller machines basically is an electromechanical version of 
this system 
we think it is something that our customers want because it 
will enable them to buy their stamps while they are getting cash 
for the weekend without needing to stand in line at a post 
office he said 
he said some surveys showed as many as half of the people 
standing in post office lines early in the morning around noon or 
in the afternoon were there simply to buy stamps 
he said the postal service had increased the number of its 
automatic vending machines and also sells stamps by mail and takes 
orders for them over the telephone the automatic teller machines 
will provide customers with another option he said 
the postal service has ordered a run of two million stamps for 
the test the spokesman said 
he said the stamps are not biodegradable but might be in the 
future 
when the stamp comes out for full national distribution we 
will probably if the technology exists and if the stamp will hold 
up consider a biodegradable product he said in fact we are 
looking to the industry and encouraging them to come out with that 
product 
