<TEXT>
the senate moved thursday toward allowing the 
nations 3 million federal civil service and postal workers to 
participate more in party politics despite a threatened veto by 
president bush 
on a 6730 vote democrats defeated an amendment by senate 
republicans aimed at derailing a bill to remove most of the 
restrictions on political activities by federal employees imposed 
by the 1939 hatch act 
the democratic bill would revise the law to lift prohibitions 
that bar federal civil service employees from holding office in 
political parties working in campaigns or soliciting campaign 
dollars from fellow workers 
however it would continue prohibitions on federal workers 
running for public office soliciting campaign funds from the 
general public or engaging in political activities while on the job 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine called the 
current restrictions illogical and unnecessary 
federal employees have been denied many of the basic rights of 
freedom of expressing and action enjoyed by millions of other 
american citizens he said citing prohibitions against 
participating in phone banks and other political operations 
the republican amendment by sen william roth rdel would 
have substituted the proposed changes with an order directing the 
office of personnel management to simplify and clarify what 
roth acknowledged are confusing regulations under the law 
roth said the bill would risk a return to the spoils system 
because civil service workers would feel compelled in the 
competition for promotions and pay raises to exercise their new 
political rights to please their politically appointed 
superior 
the house approved similar but broader legislation on a 29790 
vote more than a year ago its bill also would allow federal 
employees to seek and hold political offices and solicit campaign 
funds from the public 
congress passed nearly identical legislation in 1976 but it was 
vetoed by thenpresident gerald ford who contended it would 
politicize the civil service because workers would inevitably 
feel compelled to engage in partisan political activities 
the bush administration makes the same contention officials in 
the justice department the office of personnel management and 
white house budget office all said they would urge president bush 
to veto any change in the current law saying it would undermine 
th integrity and independence of the traditionally nonpartisan 
civil service 
the original hatch act was passed during the new deal era in 
response to overzealous political appointees of president franklin 
d roosevelt requiring enrollees in the works progress 
administration to contribute to the 1938 reelection campaign of 
then democratic sen alben barkley of kentucky 
</TEXT>
