<TEXT>
the identity of washingtons hangman can 
be kept secret a judge ruled thursday 
thurston county superior court judge daniel berschauer found 
that disclosure of the mans identity probably would block 
execution of convicted triple murderer charles rodman campbell 
prison officials believe the executioner to be the nations only 
qualified hangman and he has made it clear he will perform the job 
only if his identity and hometown are kept secret the judge said 
the undisputed evidence is that the state could not proceed 
with an execution if disclosure were made he said 
the american civil liberties union said it would quickly appeal 
the aclu had filed a request with state prison authorities 
seeking the name and qualifications of the hangman the state 
responded by suing the aclu and requesting an injunction against 
releasing the name 
campbell whose case is on appeal was sentenced to die for the 
1982 stabbing deaths of barbara hendrickson renae wicklund and 
wicklunds 8yearold daughter shannah the two women testified 
against campbell in 1976 when he was convicted of sexually 
assaulting wicklund the killings took place after he was freed 
from prison 
assistant attorney general aaron owada welcomed the decision 
both owada and the judge stressed that they support public 
disclosure as a general principle but they said state law allows a 
narrow exemption in cases where disclosure would not be in the 
public interest and would hamper a vital governmental function 
the judge said he was balancing the publics right to know with 
the right to have government run properly 
we are a society of law and if the executive branch is 
prohibited from enforcing lawful court orders such as an execution 
order then indeed there can be damage to the vital public 
interest berschauer said in ruling from the bench 
aclu attorney stephen strong told the court the information is 
in the public interest and that the prison system has issued only 
hearsay evidence that the executioner might bow out if his identity 
was released the states 1500 contract with the man says only 
that the state would try its best to keep his name secret he said 
if the state paid enough money it could find somebody 
tomorrow somebody from south africa for instance where they hang 
people all the time aclu official jerry sheehan said in a later 
interview 
the judge declined to rule on the constitutionality of hanging 
washington also allows a convict to choose death by lethal 
injection campbell has yet to indicate a preference so the state 
has to prepare for both styles of execution 
campbell came within hours of execution last year but won a 
stay from the 9th us circuit court of appeals in san francisco a 
final ruling is pending from the court 
washingtons last execution by hanging was in 1963 the last 
such execution in the nation was in iowa in 1965 
