an armycommissioned poll published thursday in 
the israel defense forces weekly indicated about 30 percent of 
israelis surveyed lacked full faith in army announcements and the 
ethical behavior of soldiers 
independent experts said this represented a significant erosion 
in public support for the army as a result of its handling of the 
palestinian uprising in which 681 palestinians and 43 israelis 
have died 
but army spokesman brig gen nachman shai said the poll showed 
a strong backing for the army 
im not satisfied with 70 percent support he said in 
an interview but after almost 29 months of intefadeh arabic for 
uprising it does speak for the basic support of the people for the 
military 
shai said he believed the credibility of army announcements had 
declined in the past two decades the result mainly of more 
aggressive and critical israeli news media 
he noted the army opened itself to more coverage and liberalized 
censorship 
people recognize it is part of democracy the price you have 
to pay he said 
the poll found 70 percent of those surveyed believed army 
statements were reliable 25 percent felt the army spokesmans 
office sometimes reliable four percent described communiques as 
unreliable no judgment was forthcoming from the remaining one 
percent 
the independent dahaf institute surveyed 1101 israeli adults 
for the poll in march ruth zin of dahaf said there was a 25 
percent margin of error 
about 70 percent of those polled also thought the army adhered 
to moral standards but it found 30 percent felt soldiers only 
conformed somewhat to ethical guidelines 
it found 95 percent believed they could rely on the armys 
combat ability 
ms zin said she could not determine whether the findings 
represented a significant change in israeli thinking since the 
questions had not been asked in previous surveys 
however independent military analysts and pollsters said the 
results pointed to a significant drop in support in a country where 
nearly everyone serves in the army and the military has 
traditionally been held in high esteem 
