<TEXT>
a military prosecutor on thursday night 
freed a local journalist whose overnight detention was criticized 
by president patricio aylwin 
a lawyer for the independent santiago daily newspaper la epoca 
luis sandoval said release of journalist manuel salazar was 
ordered by army maj raul rozas the same man who ordered his 
detention a day earlier 
salazar had uncovered the identity of a former secret police 
agent linked to the 1976 assassination in washington of former 
foreign minister orlando letelier and an american associate ronni 
moffitt 
rozas on wednesday also freed the former police agent 
the letelier case is proving to be a delicate issue for the 
elected civilian president who has pledged full cooperation 
with us officials on it and investigations into alleged human 
rights abuses during the 16year military dictatorship 
later thursday aylwin met with gen augusto pinochet for the 
first time since the rightwing army commander gave up the 
presidency in march but neither man disclosed what was discussed 
it was widely expected to include rights issues 
upon pinochets arrival at the presidential palace a small 
group of demonstrators booed him and shouted murderer two 
people were detained police said 
pinochet left the 40minute meeting through an underground exit 
avoiding reporters 
letelier was a bitter foe of pinochet three former officials in 
pinochets secret police were indicted in us courts and one of 
them admitted his role in the sept 21 1976 car bombing and served 
a sevenmonth us prison sentence 
aylwin told reporters he was surprised by the prosecutors 
order 
i think judges have the obligation to explain the reasons for 
the decisions they make he said outside his santiago residence 
the prosecutor questioned salazar for 10 hours wednesday and 
ordered he be held incommunicado indefinitely 
at the same time rozas freed the former secret agent monica 
luisa lagos 38 she had spent five days in jail while undergoing 
questioning about an alleged accessory role in the assassination of 
letelier 
questioned by reporters rozas declined to explain why he 
ordered salazars arrest he cited the secret nature of his 
investigation 
under chilean law military prosecutors can order people 
arrested during their investigations 
aylwin however said an explanation would not affect the 
secrecy of the investigation he said the action requires 
clarification from the proper authority 
salazar is national editor of la epoca and led the newspapers 
efforts to uncover the womans identity in a frontpage editorial 
under the headline our protest la epoca on thursday criticized 
the prosecutors decision as an attack on press freedom 
the woman admitted she is a former agent of a nowdefunct secret 
police agency known as dina she said she traveled to the united 
states under the assumed name of liliana walker providing cover 
for another agent who was an accomplice in the letelier slaying 
letelier was a prominent foe of pinochet who led a 1973 
military coup that overthrew the elected leftist government of 
president salvador allende 
the other two officers wanted in the letelier case are still in 
chile and us authorities say they will continue their efforts to 
bring them to justice 
on wednesday night the chilean senate unanimously approved a 
bill to posthumously restore letelier his chilean citizenship 
which the pinochet government removed 10 days before his death 
