<TEXT>
the costa rican government and 
foreign creditor banks have agreed on a formula to lower the 
central american nations 45 billion foreign debt an official 
said thursday 
eduardo lizano president of the central bank told a news 
conference that costa rica will repurchase 64 percent of its 18 
billion commercial foreign debt at 16 cents on the dollar 
the deal to be signed saturday will save costa rica 110 
million a year in debt principal and service payments he said the 
agreement was to be signed by treasury secretary rodrigo bolanos 
and representatives of the foreign banks 
once the agreement is signed costa rica will have until may 21 
to pay 253 million to bring itself up to date in payments and 
repurchase the old debt lizano said 
government officials said that costa rica has fallen behind on 
debt payments of 145 million a year however under the new 
agreement it will owe only 35 million annually 
costa rica was one of the earliest countries to reach agreement 
in principle on new financing packages under a us plan unveiled 
in march 1989 by treasury secretary nicholas brady 
it focuses on enticing commercial banks to write off some of 
their loans to third world nations or reduce the interest charged 
in return for guarantees that the remaining debt will be paid 
the strategy aimed at reducing the burder of 39 debtor 
countries emphasizes reducing a borrowing countrys debt and the 
interest it must pay by contrast the reagan administration 
strategy was to provide new loans in return for economic reforms by 
the borrowers 
</TEXT>
