<TEXT>
the united states could lose its leadership in 
superconductivity research because us companies are investing 
less in the technology than their overseas competitors according 
to a congressional study released thursday 
the office of technology assessment used hightemperature 
superconductivity as a test of the nations ability to sustain a 
longterm research and development effort said study director 
gregory eyring 
we have had a large government investment eyring said 
but if you look at the industry side the situation isnt as 
encouraging 
the primary interest is whether were ahead of the japanese 
he said 
physicist paul chu of the university of houston a pioneer in 
the field said he agreed to a certain extent with the studys 
conclusions 
us industrys involvement is certainly not as great as that 
in japan chu said wed like to see more 
the commitment from government could be even more longterm 
chu said while quantity of that commitment is important the 
quality is even more important without stability and continuity 
we cannot plan our program efficiently 
the us government spent 130 million on superconductivity 
research in 1989 while japan spent less than 70 million the study 
said but japanese companies in late 1988 and early 1989 invested 
about 107 million in such research compared with about 73 million 
by us firms it said 
superconductors have no resistance to the flow of electricity 
if they could be harnessed in ordinary electrical devices they 
could avoid the energy lost to heating in the generation and 
distribution of power 
so far the principal uses of superconductors are in magnets in 
medical imaging devices and particle accelerators 
superconductivity was discovered in 1911 but for years 
superconductors were only known to work when cooled by liquid 
helium to a few degrees above absolute zero minus 459 degrees 
fahrenheit 
in 1986 chu discovered a superconductor that worked at minus 
234 degrees fahrenheit a temperature reached with cheap liquid 
nitrogen and higher temperatures have been reported since 
the ota study said hightemperature superconductivity should 
receive a higher priority at universities than it does now 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

