<TEXT>
bonds are not the only junk peddled in the 
securities markets there are junk companies too financed by junk 
bonds there is plenty of junk analysis too 
ask the folks who make up the housing and real estate markets 
those people who have had to read one brokerage house analysis 
after another about how it no longer pays to own a home junky 
analysis they say 
as an investment the wall street analysts contend housing has 
had it prices have run up so far that buyers have been priced out 
of the market the demographics are turning therell be a slowdown 
in buyingage population 
many of the analyses including some from academe have been the 
basis of stories about the great housing bust the coming collapse 
of housing prices the ominous recession in real estate crumbling 
castles and the like 
such notions so irritated the national association of home 
builders that it countered with a special report pointing out that 
housing is not a security is not wildly traded is more than an 
investment and has basic innate value 
it has not stopped wall street a brokerage house analysis just 
issued grows enthusiastic about the demise of the singlefamily 
home as the american familys primary investment now it suggests 
people will turn to securities 
the analyst contends that adjusted for quality and price 
change the average american homeowner is worse off today than he 
or she was in 1980 
really housing people ask 
in 1980 the median price of singlefamily homes was 64000 by 
late last year just before the decade closed the median was more 
than 125000 or close to double an increase greater than 
inflation in general 
this after putting up just 10 percent of the price living in 
the house for a decade watching children grow up enjoying unique 
income tax deductions having the use of lowcost equity loans 
paying down the mortgage 
the reality of home price underperformance in the 1980s has 
been very slow to sink in many people clung and in some instances 
still cling to the expectations of renewed appreciation the 
analysis continues 
perhaps they do but meanwhile they have a roof over their heads 
and a foundation under their feet which is more than can be said 
for some of the junk companies that wall street recommended in the 
1980s 
but why housing industry people ask should home prices 
collapse or barely keep pace with inflation because say wall 
streets analysts housing has been priced beyond the means of 
buyers prices must fall to meet the market 
maybe so but isnt the market there those same analysts have 
been saying for years that millions of americans couldnt afford 
houses and it is unlikely that they will have disappeared at the 
very time opportunity arrives 
but the analysts say the youngfamily bulge that supported 
homebuying in the 1980s will flatten in the 1990s yes say the 
housing people and that means builders probably wont build as 
many houses as in the 1980s 
aside from these considerations the home builders point out 
other salient considerations that tend to support prices 
buildable land the biggest single factor in housing costs is 
not growing in supply if anything building and environmental 
codes may become even more strict labor costs arent likely to 
plunge 
while people dont necessarily need stocks and bonds and from 
time to time foresake the markets in them they do need homes most 
people wouldnt be caught without one 
</TEXT>
