<TEXT>
nancy cruzan lies comatose in a 
southwestern missouri hospital bed steven goodwin a federal 
prisoner in springfield wants to impregnate his wife by artificial 
insemination heath wilkins sits on death row in potosi fighting 
execution for a murder he committed at age 16 
these three court cases all from missouri have reached the 
us supreme court or are headed that way 
along with the high courts rulings last july on abortion and in 
april on school desegregation they have thrust missouri into the 
legal limelight to an extent perhaps unmatched by any other state 
today 
doctors say cruzan 32 in a coma since a 1983 car accident 
could live an additional 30 years with no hope of recovery her 
parents want to remove her feeding tube so she can die as they 
believe she would want the missouri supreme court refused to allow 
it and now the us supreme court is deciding the issue in its 
first righttodie case the decision is expected by july 
wilkins 21 also known as inmate number cp47 spends his days 
with 69 other missouri death row convicts at the potosi 
correctional center while he fights to get the courts to overturn 
his death sentence 
at least one argument no longer is open to him last year the 
supreme court used his case to rule that states could execute 
killers who commit their crimes at age 16 thats how old wilkins 
was when he walked into a kansas cityarea liquor store in 1985 and 
killed a clerk during a robbery 
in the abortion case the supreme court last july voted 54 to 
restore key provisions of a restrictive missouri law allowing it 
and all other states to ban any public employee from helping 
perform an abortion and to ban abortions in all public hospitals 
the court also ruled that states may require doctors to determine 
whether a 20weekold fetus was capable of surviving outside the 
womb 
the high court recently used a kansas city case to say federal 
judges may order local officials to raise property taxes to pay for 
desegregation of public schools judges however cant impose tax 
increases themselves the justices said 
the judicial pipeline from missouri to washington remains wide 
open 
goodwin 32 serving 14 years on drug charges at the us 
medical center for federal prisoners in springfield wants to 
impregnate his wife by artificial insemination the federal bureau 
of prisons has refused to allow it 
all we are asking for is a clean container and a swift 
messenger said goodwins attorney ronald kuby of new york 
goodwins appeal is before the 8th us circuit court of appeals 
the last stop before the supreme court 
observers suggest missouris sudden surge to the legal forefront 
is a combination of timing coincidence the courts growing 
conservatism and the tendency of the missouri legislature to pass 
laws that invite challenge 
we have been at the right place at the right time said 
missouri attorney general william webster and we have a supreme 
court that is interested in hearing the issues and that 
combination has permitted missouri to be aggressive 
he said the court seems more willing to consider cases that have 
not been fully litigated in the federal circuits around the 
country the cruzan case is an example 
twenty years ago it is very doubtful they would have ever 
reached out and said were interested from the federal case 
law its a brand new issue webster said 
he said the court took the wilkins case along with a kentucky 
case involving a 17yearold after the justices in 1988 overturned 
the death sentence for a 15yearold in an oklahoma case they said 
the death penalty is a constitutional punishment for murderers who 
committed their crimes at age 16 but not for killers younger than 
that 
i think it was an attempt to draw the line webster said 
as for abortion webster who personally argued the case before 
the justices said the court chose missouri over three other cases 
i think there was little doubt the new court was interested in 
revisiting the issue of abortion he said arguably ours was 
the narrowest of the four the court took this as a tentative step 
rather than a fulltilt reversal of its 1973 decision legalizing 
abortion 
beyond the laws are those challenging them in the courts 
beginning the process that ends at the supreme court 
state rep jim barnes who sponsored the bill that became the 
states challenged 1986 abortion law says whenever laws are made 
there are those ready to fight them 
missourians tend to make conservative laws which are ripe for 
challenge said barnes a democrat diversity generates 
conflicts and conflicts create court cases 
joyce armstrong executive director of the american civil 
liberties unions eastern missouri office agrees many missouri 
laws lend themselves to legal challenge the aclu represented 
reproductive health services inc of st louis which filed the 
original lawsuit in the abortion case 
it was lobbied very hard by the antiabortion groups she 
said of the missouri legislature they felt missouri was a likely 
state legislature that would pass such a restrictive law 
