<TEXT>
for 10000 years people lived with the 
mississippi river and its contradictions the certainty of periodic 
floods that can wash whole settlements away the uncertainty of the 
rivers shifting course which may abandon them in its delta 
poverty has compounded natures challenges for generations yet 
millions call the lifegiving lifetaking river home who are 
they what holds them an associated press reporter followed 1000 
miles of old man river to try to find out 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in the towns along the lower mississippi from around cairo 
ill to below new orleans theres lots of talk about the good old 
days 
cairo had the highest per capita wealth anywhere they say of 
course that was 100 years ago 
in a louisiana town called waterproof people remember saturday 
night crowds so thick you had to walk through the street 
sideways 
nostalgia is hardly unique to the mississippi delta but in this 
region it may help reconcile the paradoxes that show up everywhere 
this is a place after all where the pain of slave labor took 
sweet expression in the words and rhythms of the blues 
in towns long abandoned by river trade and plantation society 
harkening back is looking ahead an antebellum mansion on a river 
bluff or an ersatz showboat may bring in tourist dollars a hope 
for the future 
just after dawn in cairo a towboats engine hums as it pushes 
barges against the current birds twitter and daniel hartmanns 
shotgun echoes on commercial street downtown with city officials 
blessing he blasts pigeons from rooftops and window ledges 
long gone are the human inhabitants of many buildings on the 
boulevard which bustles in old photographs hartmann explains hes 
just trying to keep the birds from taking over 
a mile away a community group tries to keep despair from taking 
over 
the focus of operation enterprise is the wedge of land where the 
ohio river joins the mississippi fort defiance stood here and 
ulysses s grant directed operations on the river in the civil war 
grant triumphed but a park on the site surrendered to neglect a 
few years ago a headline called it the ugliest park in america 
that became a spur not just to save the park but to put cairo 
through a selfanalysis says angela greenwell a leader of 
operation enterprise 
weve identified our problems she says and they sound 
familiar in the delta region lingering racial divisions in the 
town of 4500 poverty unemployment an attitude of resignation 
about it all 
inventorying cairos assets operation enterprise listed the 
confluence of the rivers considerable history willing workers and 
a friendly southern style that led to development plans first a 
showboatmall complex then citywide restoration finally a theme 
park 
the tourists may or may not come but the group has launched 
other projects including an ambulance service and has brought 
blacks and whites together it also has maintained the park that 
started it all undiscouraged when the water rises as it did this 
spring and covers their work in mud we are survivors mrs 
greenwell says 
across a bridge from cairo a sign tells travelers theyve 
entered kentucky open for business it adds hopefully 
and there is big business on the big river more than 420 
million tons of cargo a year moves on barges 
coal grain fertilizer sugar jim york a barge line 
dispatcher in columbus ky runs off the commodities carried by 
barges like those tied up in the channel outside his window 
alcohol chemicals diesel fuel gas 
once he saw human cargo 12 flattop barges the kind used for 
hauling rock carrying national guardsmen whod pitched their tents 
on deck looked like a big party going upriver 
every so often the radio on yorks desk picks up a familiar 
voice his fathers jim sr is a towboat captain 
they say if you wear out your first pair of boots out there 
youll be out there all your life the son says 
on the gentle hills that slope down to the river hawks perch in 
dead trees that look like antennas real antennas pick up gospel 
stations playbyplay of stock car races country songs 
im seein my father in me 
guess thats how its meant to be 
ronnie and tammy harpers modest house occupies a rise outside 
clinton ky my parents live in the fifth house on the right her 
daddys across the road says ronnie a carpenter who often does 
remodeling work for retirees settling in the area 
as older folks move in many people in their 20s the harpers 
age group are moving away looking for jobs or for a change from 
the pace that can be as predictable as the rivers flow 
not the harpers they figured on staying put even before their 
first child christopher was born feb 28 
and when he grows up where would they like him to settle 
next door would be fine says the new father 
like other kids hell probably play and fish on the sandbar 
here that is if the river doesnt swallow it for centuries the 
twisting mississippi has straightened and shortened itself by 
carving cutoffs that eliminate bends 
towns like millikens bend and hopefield ark are gone washed 
away as the river shifted course others have had to scramble to 
higher ground towns like ste genevieve and new madrid mo have 
relocated several times 
below new madrid lies the busy farming center and river port of 
caruthersville mo where barges are built and the downtown 
uniform is overalls 
here the mann family plies the oldest trade on the river 
dorothy manns husband john and son byron catch the fish son 
mike runs the shop 
its true mike says that a few customers concerned about 
contamination have walked out when they learned the fish wasnt 
farmraised 
many parts of the mississippi have grown cleaner in recent 
years with sewage treatment and other improvements but toxic 
materials remain in the sediment and fishing is restricted in 
places 
still most folks who walk into manns want a taste of the river 
or even something wilder like coon we cooked eight for 
christmas here mike mann says coons delicious if you fix it 
right 
downriver a ways memphis tenn offers a different taste of 
the mississippi the city still bills itself as a party town 
memphis is where wc handy migrated with music called the blues 
and beale street today pulses to updated urban variations 
the city was also the royal court when cotton was king trucks 
laden with burlapbound bales of cotton still lumber up front 
street but says cotton buyer chris hill as workers gather up 
fluffy sweepings left by graders in one warehouse many big brokers 
have moved away its not like it used to be hill says 
