<TEXT>
cutting the dropout rate is one of six goals 
named by president bush and the nations governors in their effort 
to improve american schools the following report the first in a 
periodic ap series examining those goals shows how a tough high 
school in the phoenix barrio managed to lower its rate dramatically 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
two years ago south mountain high school was 
just another struggling school in the citys toughest section 
known only for violence and a stubbornly high dropout rate of 22 
percent 
every time i met somebody theyd say god you actually go to 
south said rick bouwense an 18yearold junior 
but this school year fewer than 10 percent of south mountains 
kids dropped out 
suddenly dramatically against all odds south mountain is 
gaining national attention as an innercity school that is solving 
one of educations toughest dilemmas how to keep students in 
school especially poor minority youngsters 
in february the bush administration and the national governors 
association listed six goals for improving us schools near the 
top was cutting the nations dropout rate to less than 10 percent 
by the year 2000 
if south mountain holds a lesson for other schools struggling to 
cut the dropout rate it is this you need money but you need 
much much more 
the bottom line at south mountain was convincing students the 
school was safe and that it had the desire to give more than lip 
service to individual students needs to do that the school 
totally restructured itself in the last two years it now has the 
look and feel of few others 
teachers spend only half the day in class the rest of the time 
they tutor kids 
students who once worried about being scorned as bookworms dont 
have to tote texts between school and home south mountain spent 
100000 just to provide extra copies for homework 
four dazzlingly equipped magnet schools attract students from 
around the city to study law aerospace the performing arts and 
visual arts and overall standards were raised to eliminate dummy 
courses like consumer math 
the school hired 70 extra teachers and added counselors 
including several who put students and parents with social or 
health problems in touch with appropriate city agencies 
and in a particularly vital step south mountain reversed its 
citywide reputation as a cauldron of violence by hiring additional 
security guards and stripping hallways of student lockers to reduce 
hiding places for contraband 
judged by statistics alone the national dropout rate defined 
as the number of 16to24yearolds without high school degrees 
has steadily improved in 1968 the us rate was 162 percent it 
now stands at 129 percent 
innercity schools however generally have much higher dropout 
rates in philadelphia for example a study released in march 
found that only 41 percent of students who entered high school in 
1984 had earned diplomas 
no comparable statebystate figures exist because states 
havent agreed on a single method for collecting dropout data 
but a recent study by brandeis university researchers concluded 
that the southwest with its large migrant and immigrant 
population has the worst regional problem southwestern states as 
a group have a dropout rate of 21 percent compared with 18 percent 
in the northeast 11 percent in the southeast and 9 percent in the 
northwest 
south mountains apparent successes havent come cheaply or 
easily 
the school lies on whats often called the wrong side of the 
dry salt river bed that divides the impoverished south side from 
the rest of phoenix crack crime and los angelesbased gangs like 
the crips and bloods have infiltrated the neighborhood 
its student body of 2700 is 54 percent hispanic 31 percent 
black and the remainder mostly anglo 
many come from troubled backgrounds as many as 200 girls get 
pregnant each year many students consider dropping out at some 
point some do like 16yearold mark 
a cherubiclooking sophomore mark dropped out of south mountain 
twice this year missing several months of school and spending idle 
hours messing around the neighborhood 
he fell in with bad company started stealing cars and wound up 
on probation just after christmas mark was shot in the foot in a 
driveby incident 
a school counselor visited several times and late in march 
mark decided to give south mountain another try 
nearly everyone here agrees that south mountain wouldnt have 
gotten very far in its dropout effort if not for the 17 million a 
year in desegregation money that has come its way on average for 
the last five years 
the money raised through a special local tax is the result of 
a 1984 federal courtordered plan to make phoenix schools more 
racially balanced 
the court gave the district wide latitude in how to spend the 
money as long as it met the goal of attracting students of all 
races to segregated schools 
south mountain spent some of its windfall on new security guards 
it was important for us to send an appropriate message said 
coprincipal art lebowitz that we do not tolerate weapons no 
gang colors no drugs no nonstudents on campus 
so far this year three weapons have been confiscated down from 
an average of five and students and teachers say drugs and 
violence are now a rarity 
much of the desegregation money was used to hire the new 
teachers and counselors and a second principal 
students say they can tell the difference 
joanne blank a sophomore who had considered dropping out 
recalls once approaching lebowitz to talk over a problem he was 
talking to a teacher but he interrupted that to talk to me she 
said he told me students come first 
people here dont wait til you hit rock bottom til they do 
something she said 
an early milestone for south mountain came five years ago when 
it opened its magnet schools as in other school districts under 
desegregation orders the hope was that such schools would attract 
whites from around the city 
today students can get private dance and music lessons at the 
performing arts school which also has a recording studio with 
professional sound mixing equipment 
the law magnet features a classroom mockup of a courtroom 
complete with a judges bench spectator gallery and a well for 
lawyers and stenographers 
this spring students combined lessons in law and literature 
when they put shakespeares romeo on mock trial the verdict 
innocent of the charge of disturbing the princes peace 
sixteenyearold hector quijada a dropout last fall returned 
to south mountain and is now preparing for a career in tv 
production in a stateoftheart studio that cost more than 1 
million to equip 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

