<DOCNO> AP900503-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
ive gone from fs and ds to cs and bs said quijada who 
also has a parttime job as a cameraman at a local tv station 
despite their outward dazzle however the magnets had only 
limited impact on the dropout problem by 1987 the schools 
dropout rate had fallen from about 25 percent to 22 percent 
the sluggish progress convinced phoenixs thensuperintendent 
timothy dyer that the school had to do more than buy flashy 
equipment south mountain had to break with the past 
ultimately we decided to radically restructure the school 
teachers simply couldnt deal effectively with 150 kids a day we 
have to deal with the whole child including the social realm 
dyer said 
dyer and others devised a fiveyear south mountain plan now 
in its second year again using desegregation money the school 
increased its teacher staff from 150 to 220 
key to the plans success was an agreement reached with the 
local teachers union temporarily waiving seniority rules to allow 
south mountain to handpick the new teachers 
just as crucially administrators restructured the school day to 
give teachers fewer classes and create special hours when 
youngsters could seek out tutors or make up missing work 
just raising expectations alone is absolute poppycock cutting 
the dropout rate takes a multifaceted program said dyer now 
executive director of the national association of secondary school 
principals in reston va 
south mountain also raised standards for the first time last 
fall all freshmen were required to take algebra 
as teachers we all think its working said kathy anderson 
who teaches firstyear math it gives kids more confidence and 
selfesteem 
at first they look at the work and say i cant do algebra 
then after two weeks they say thats all there is to it 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lee mitgang has covered education for the 
associated press since 1981 
