<TEXT>
the debate continues over what federal 
regulatory agency should oversee financial products that cross the 
line between securities and futures 
reps dennis eckart dohio and dan glickman dkan have 
sponsored a bill that would merge the feuding securities and 
exchange commission and the commodity futures trading commission 
into a single markets and trading commission 
glickman was slated to explain the bill in testimony before a 
house subcommittee today 
the idea has some highpowered opposition though 
on wednesday federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan said 
he was uncomfortable with the idea of concentrating regulatory 
authority into single agency 
there have been calls for either merging the two agencies or 
giving the sec authority over stock index futures financial 
products that allow investors to speculate in the stock market 
without having to buy the underlying stocks currently they are 
regulated by the cftc 
one choice with which i feel uncomfortable is the 
concentration of regulatory authority in a single agency 
greenspan said in a luncheon speech to a joint conference of the 
cftc and the futures industry institute 
i am concerned that the costs could well outweigh the benefits 
from a simpler decisionmaking process the head of the nations 
top economic policymaking body said 
earlier wednesday cftc chairman wendy gramm said wall street 
jealousy was behind the push to give the rival sec some or all of 
her agencys jurisdiction 
there are two motives gramm said in the keynote speech 
first the sec wants more regulatory power 
she added that some on wall street want to turn back the clock 
to an earlier time because the securities sector is jealous of 
the performace and market share of the futures market 
she continued rather than compete directly with financially 
innovative firms and products or respond to a fastchanging 
economic landscape they under the umbrella of the sec want to 
regain better times simply by grabbing the success of the futures 
market 
an offandon feud between the sec which regulates stocks and 
bonds and the cftc which oversees the futures industry has been 
escalating recently over who should have jurisdiction over 
hybrid financial products such as stock index futures 
gramm said effort that should be spent on market reform is 
being sidetracked by this unproductive timeconsuming and 
competitively damaging turf fight 
the debate over jurisdiction has heated up unquestionably 
said greenspan the outcome could affect the longterm health of 
our markets including the ability of domestic markets to maintain 
their role as a leader in creating innovative products 
hybrid products have elements of both securities and futures 
contracts a federal appeals court has said the cftc has authority 
over anything with the slightest element of a futures contract 
that has prompted sec chairman richard c breeden to complain 
that the split regulatory authority is driving financial innovation 
out of the united states and letting foreign markets trade in 
copycat hybrid products 
but gramm said splitting off stock index futures from cftc 
jurisdiction would only hurt the overall futures market 
eliminating this exclusive jurisdiction could result in 
regulatory chaos by allowing futures which all have the same 
economic purpose to be regulated under multiple and different 
regulatory systems she said in one of her sharpest criticisms of 
attempts to limit cftc authority 
</TEXT>
