<TEXT>
top trade officials from three continents 
are holding what are described as freewheeling discussions aimed at 
breaking a stalemate in the most ambitious round of global trade 
talks ever undertaken 
us trade representative carla hills leader of the american 
delegation warned that failure of the freetrade talks could 
sentence all countries of the world to gravely diminished 
prosperity 
the talks which began with a dinner wednesday and conclude 
friday were being held at a posh country club and resort in the 
heart of california wine country they involve japan european 
countries and canada along with the united states 
hills who set the agenda for the meeting told reporters that 
rather than have the delegations read position papers she had 
drawn up a detailed set of questions she hoped would prompt an 
exchange of ideas on how to resolve their differences 
i dont want to have a script read to me she said adding 
that the informal talks were meant to be more freewheeling than 
structured 
the bush administration has made successful completion of the 
multinational talks its top trade priority it hopes that freer 
world trade will expand overseas sales by american farmers and 
businesses and thus reduce the huge us trade deficit 
the trade talks which involve close to 100 countries began in 
uruguay in 1986 and are being conducted under the auspices of the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade or gatt 
while many believe the gatt rules governing trade are badly in 
need of modernization the differences over how to accomplish this 
are so great there is fear the talks could fail 
the administration is pushing to scrap costly agricultural 
subsidies predicting such a move would boost us farm sales by 
11 billion annually this effort is opposed by the 12nation 
european community which wants to protect its smallersized farms 
the united states would also like to see tougher safeguards 
enacted to prevent patent and trademark piracy which costs 
american companies 60 billion annually 
however third world countries such as india are objecting to 
this proposal developing countries also take issue with another 
american aim to expand gatt rules to cover trade in services such 
as banking and insurance 
developing nations see huge multinational companies as a threat 
to their infant service industries 
hills said the industrial countries had to keep promoting the 
idea that open markets would expand investment in third world 
countries and lead to greater prosperity 
speaking to a group of business writers in san francisco on 
wednesday before the trade talks opened she called the 
negotiations the last best chance this century to create the 
trading rules we so sorely need for the next century 
hills painted failure of the talks in stark terms of diminished 
living standards for both industrial and developing countries 
down one path lie open markets expanded trade economic 
growth and prosperity she said down the other lie closed 
markets nations turned inward and gravely diminished prosperity 
for all 
hills said she was hopeful the three days of discussions would 
provide enough guidance to allow lowerlevel negotiators to draft a 
preliminary text at a july 23 bargaining session in geneva 
switzerland that in turn could serve as a basis for clearing up 
as many issues as possible before the scheduled final round of 
discussions dec 37 in brussels 
the trade talks are also on the agenda for the sevennation 
economic summit to be held in houston in july 
hills said she believed it would be very helpful for bush and 
the other world leaders to give a political push to the 
negotiating effort 
