<TEXT>
prime minister mahathir mohamad 
doesnt like the idea but booming malaysia may soon exit the third 
world and join the ranks of newly industrialized countries 
its newly industrialized neighbors in asia south korea 
taiwan hong kong and singapore are known as the regions 
economic dragons despite robust growth malaysia remains a 
reluctant dragon 
tiny malaysia has evolved from a simple producer of tropical 
crops into an emerging economic force that manufactures products 
ranging from cars to computer chips its central bank forecasts 
growth of more than 8 percent in 1990 for the third consecutive 
year 
foreign businessmen and other analysts say malaysia is 
competitive in southeast asia in the quality and cost of labor 
infrastructure repatriation of profits attitude toward foreign 
investment overall cost of doing business and political stability 
so why the reluctance 
a key reason is official fear that developed countries will 
classify malaysia as a socalled newly developed country or nic 
which could mean an end to trading concessions that have enabled 
malaysian exporters to do so well 
the government also fears trade retaliation from the united 
states and other rich powers who could demand environmental and 
human right standards they deem acceptable to developed countries 
mahathir has described the label newly industrializing 
country as an arbitrary western notion applied by the developed 
world that may curb economic growth in developing nations 
a country risks penalties as a nic when it industrializes and 
its citizens attain a higher standard of living he said trading 
privileges such as reduced tariffs under the generalized system of 
preferences are taken away quotas are slapped on exports and the 
domestic currency increases in value making it harder for 
exporters to do business 
the chances are that these countries will languish in their 
nic status and never become fully developed mahathir said 
because their competitiveness and access to markets is curtailed 
we are interested in growing but they can keep the title and 
what goes with it mahathir said it is just that we do not 
like categorization and labels aimed at limiting our future 
growth 
he said the human rights record of a designated nic is examined 
and invariably found wanting 
malaysia already has been criticized by foreign labor groups for 
its policy toward union organizing in 1988 for example the 
aflcio sought unsuccessfully to have malaysias preferential 
trading status with the united states canceled the us labor 
group contended that malaysian electronics workers only could join 
inhouse unions 
in addition malaysia has been criticized for years for the 
indiscriminate logging of its tropical rain forest mahathir says 
the critics are illinformed or selfserving 
the thinning of the ozone layer is blamed on logging of 
tropical forests the fact that the burning of fossil fuels and 
release of cfcs chlorofluorocarbons into the atmosphere occur 
largely in the rich countries are significantly ignored he told 
an international conference in october 
mahathir concedes that his country will one day be recognized as 
an nic regardless of his wishes based on recent performance that 
day may be approaching fast 
manufacturing investment last year increased 579 percent to the 
equivalent of 744 billion said trade and industry minister 
rafidah aziz foreign investment rose 308 percent last year to 
497 billion while domestic investment climbed 110 percent to 
337 billion 
even without manufacturing malaysia has long been recognized as 
one of the luckier developing lands with a balanced array of 
resources a leading exporter of natural rubber palm oil and tin 
it is also an important source of cocoa pepper tropical 
hardwoods crude oil and natural gas 
industry was introduced in the 1960s with small assembly plants 
and processing of some crops motor vehicles were assembled from 
completely knocked down kits 
exportoriented manufacturing started in the 1970s led by 
semiconductor companies about 100000 people are employed in 
electronics the driving force behind the changeover from a 
commodity producer to a manufacturing power 
malaysia is now the biggest exporter of semiconductor devices 
and the third largest producer after japan and the united states 
members of the malaysianamerican electronics industry group which 
represents 15 us firms have about 40000 workers in 18 plants 
the united states is a leading foreign investor in malaysia 
domestic companies with us participation had assets totaling 6 
billion at the end of 1988 a large number of them are usowned 
end adv for monday may 7 
