<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has placed limits on who 
can be prosecuted for insider trading overturning the conviction 
of a stockbroker who traded on fourthhand information about the 
pending takeover of waldbaum inc 
the decision wednesday by the 2nd us circuit court of appeals 
also guts a key securities and exchange commission regulation used 
to prosecute anyone who trades on misappropriated information about 
a takeover 
the court unanimously said it found no evidence that former 
stockbroker robert chestman knew that information about the 1986 
sale of the supermarket chain which he received down a chain of 
family members was confidential 
after passing through several family channels it cannot be 
said that the information was confidential to any degree or was any 
more than family gossip the court said 
more important securities experts said was a 21 decision that 
guts rule 14e3 of the securities exchange act which makes it a 
crime to trade on inside information about a takeover even if the 
trading doesnt violate a fiduciary duty to a company 
the rule has been used frequently to prosecute insider trading 
cases involving takeovers in the 1980s the appeals court ruling 
essentially means the government will have to prove the defendant 
knew the information was stolen 
insider trading lacks a statutory definition but generally 
refers to buying or selling securities on the basis of 
confidential nonpublic information 
the chestman case had expanded securities law interpretation to 
encompass disclosure of secrets down a chain and hinged on whether 
chestman had a fiduciary dury to waldbaum inc no prior criminal 
case had involved confidential information passed among family 
members 
chestman who began serving his twoyear prison sentence last 
june was released from a minimumsecurity prison in allenwood 
pa wednesday evening and returned to his long island home 
chestman attorney elkan abramowitz said 
the us attorneys office was reviewing the ruling and had not 
decided on whether to appeal to the supreme court or for an 
appellate court rehearing spokeswoman deborah corley said 
according to testimony at chestmans trial ira waldbaum agreed 
in 1986 to sell the grocery business founded by his grandfather in 
1921 to the great atlantic amp pacific tea co better known as aampp 
for 50 a share or 287 million 
he told his sister shirley witkin about the deal stressing 
that the information had to remain confidential until it was 
announced publicly witkin informed her daughter susan loeb who 
in turn told her husband keith 
keith loeb then told chestman who bought 11000 shares of 
waldbaum inc for about 25 each making overnight profits of 
250000 for himself and several clients including loeb 
the securities and exchange commission alerted to the trading 
by routine postmerger stock market surveillance filed civil 
charges loeb cooperated with investigators 
chestman was charged criminally and convicted by a jury in may 
1989 on 31 counts the civil charges still are pending 
chestmans attorneys said he had decided to serve the prison 
term before his appeal was decided because he felt he couldnt get 
a job until the case was behind him 
