<TEXT>
trade negotiators reported no major 
breakthroughs thursday in their effort to resolve disagreements 
that threaten to derail an ambitious effort to reform the global 
trading system 
trade ministers from the united states japan the 12nation 
european community and canada held a second day of discussions 
behind closed doors at a resort in the california wine country 
the united states is seeking to boost export opportunities for 
american farmers and business by getting agreement to eliminate 
expensive farm export subsidies to eliminate barriers to trade in 
services and to toughen restrictions on copyright and trademark 
piracy 
a us trade official briefing reporters on condition that his 
name not be used said there was some progress toward better 
defining the areas of disagreement but no success at resolving the 
major disputes 
the biggest fight involves the american effort to end 
tradedistorting agricultural subsidies something the european 
community opposes 
the talks were scheduled to conclude after a final bargaining 
session on friday 
the bush adminisration has made the negotiations its top trade 
priority insisting that expanded export opportunities will help 
significantly reduce americas huge trade deficit 
the discussions which are being conducted under the auspices of 
the 97nation general agreement on tariffs and trade began in 
uruguay in 1986 
trade representative carla hills who is leading the us team 
said she was optimistic differences can be narrowed but many fear 
that unless there are significant compromises soon the fouryear 
effort will end unsuccessfully at the final bargaining session dec 
37 in brussels 
hills and the other trade ministers hoped the california talks 
would provide the guidance for lowerlevel negotiators to put 
together a tentative agreement in many of the areas during a july 
bargaining session in geneva 
there has to be substantial agreeement by july said 
canadian trade minister john crosbie who warned that failure of 
the gatt talks would result in an international trade shambles 
the european community is strongly resisting american demands 
for a total phaseout of agricultural subsidies arguing it must 
protect its small farms 
third world countries are fighting the proposals to clamp down 
on copyright piracy and break down barriers to trade in services 
arguing the developing world needs to protect its infant industries 
against huge multinational companies 
the administration claims copyright and trademark piracy costs 
us companies 60 billion annually 
in addition to pushing its proposals in the gatt talks the 
administration is being forced to battle special interest groups in 
the united states that stand to lose trade protections as well 
legislation has been introduced in congress to retain textile 
industry barriers against foreign imports peanut growers and sugar 
producers who benefit from special subsidies that limit foreign 
competition are also working to build congressional opposition 
hills has countered that american farm groups stand to gain much 
more than they will lose through eliminating other countries 
barriers she said exports of us farm products could rise by 11 
billion annually an amount equal to 3400 for every american 
farmer 
speaking to reporters after thursdays session hills said 
working groups would examine a number of issues in the hope of 
narrowing differences further before the start of fridays final 
session 
we made constructive progress she said of the talks so far 
crosbie put the chances for ultimate success at better than 
5050 because the consequences of failure are so horrific 
but the canadian trade minister said progress at this stage was 
measured by very small steps in a number of areas 
you cant put your finger on any specific thing and say it is 
a great leap forward he said 
republican gov george deukmejian of california addressing a 
luncheon for the trade ministers defended the administrations 
freetrade policies saying that competition was good for american 
industry and consumers 
from agriculture and aerospace to electronics and 
entertainment californians have created markets worldwide he 
said we engage the competition abroad and welcome it at home 
for trade stimulates innovation and delivers better products at 
lower prices 
