<TEXT>
farm debt declined for a sixth straight 
year in 1989 to an 11year low and the quality of farm loans 
improved the federal reserve bank of chicago estimates 
most analysts expect the downward trend in debt to halt this 
year though fed economist gary benjamin said 
benjamin estimated total farm debt declined nearly 2 percent in 
1989 to 1356 billion from 1384 billion a year earlier he based 
the figure on recent reports from major farm lending institutions 
and a preliminary us department of agriculture assessment of farm 
loans held by all other lenders 
commercial banks are the largest source of loans to farmers 
accounting for a third of all farm debt 
the total for 1989 includes approximately 743 billion in farm 
loans secured by real estate a drop of 3 percent from 1988 
the remaining 613 billion in loans primarily reflected 
borrowing for farm operations and equipment and was down less than 
1 percent from the previous year 
compared to 1983 peaks both real estate and nonreal estate 
loans were down about 30 percent benjamin said in an agricultural 
letter published by the chicago fed 
while the 1980s marked a decade during which farm debt fell 
substantially following a period of widespread financial distress 
most analysts are looking for a modest upturn in farm debt this 
year benjamin said reflecting the painful lessons learned 
during the financial distress of a few years ago both lenders and 
farm borrowers remain cautious with respect to new borrowings 
prospects for another year of strong net cash farm earnings 
particularly in the midwest suggest that repayments on existing 
farm debts will remain favorable and that many farmers will 
continue to rely heavily on internally generated funds to cover new 
expenditures at the same time however prospects for further but 
modest gains in farmland values and farm operating expenses 
coupled with the continuing rebound in expenditures for farm 
machinery and equipment imply farm loan demand will be somewhat 
stronger this year benjamin said 
he also reported that the quality of loans on the books of 
commercial lenders improved last year 
for banks such improvements are reflected in smaller charges 
against earnings for bad loans and a drop in the proportion of 
delinquent loans 
net chargeoffs of farm loans by banks nationwide last year 
declined to less than 100 million from 140 million in 1989 and an 
annual average of 12 billion from 198486 
</TEXT>
