<TEXT>
no recession is in sight for the united states 
and other industrial countries things are looking up in the third 
world and eastern europe could become a source of dynamism for the 
world the international monetary fund said thursday 
the fund projected a rosy future in its semiannual world 
economic outlook provided governments carry out the kind of 
policies it wants to see lower budget deficits balanced world 
trade privatization of governmentowned business 
it predicts world production will grow 225 percent this year 
and accelerate to a 3 percent growth rate in 1991 that would match 
last years rate but still be behind the 4 percent growth posted in 
1988 
the industrialized countries should grow by 27 percent this 
year the fund predicts that is down slightly from its forecast 
last fall of 29 percent growth 
japan should lead the growth parade of the major industrial 
countries with a 44 percent rate this year and 42 percent in 
1991 for 1990 west germany should be in second place at 35 
percent but yield that position to france and canada in 1991 which 
are expected to grow 31 percent that year 
officials warned however that their figures could not take 
full account of german unification german forecasts expect that to 
be a sharp spur to growth 
the united states the worlds biggest economy is expected to 
lag behind with a 17 percent growth rate this year and 23 percent 
next year 
the latest 1990 forecasts for the united states and japan are 
down from last fall when the fund predicted growth of 21 percent 
and 47 percent respectively the forecast of 35 percent growth 
for west germany this year is up from last falls prediction of 30 
percent however 
the fund classes only 22 countries among its 152 members as 
industrial 
it lumps east asian tigers like south korea with laggards in 
africa and latin america as developing countries the report 
forecast their production will rise 3 percent this year 45 
percent next year by 1995 the growth rate for these countries 
should be at the 5 percent level last seen in the 1970s 
the increase in growth projected for these countries rests 
heavily on the assumption that adjustment policies are successful 
in bringing down inflation and improving the climate for domestic 
savings and investment the report said 
but it saw little scope for africa to recoup its losses of 
income in the 1980s leaders in both africa and latin american 
often speak of the 1980s as a lost decade 
the funds rosiest forecast was for asia 57 percent growth 
next year despite a downward revision for china 
it also predicted a marked improvement in growth rates for 
eastern europe though the uncertainties of recent changes and 
those to come made it wary of exact projections 
with their relatively skilled work forces the countries of 
eastern europe could emerge as a source of dynamism for europe and 
to a lesser extent for the world economy it said 
</TEXT>
