<TEXT>
pennsylvania has offered unemployment benefits 
to striking greyhound lines inc bus drivers and mechanics a move 
company officials claimed made the state the first in the nation to 
do so 
labor secretary harris wofford announced the payments which 
will affect about 300 pennsylvania strikers at the aflcios state 
convention in pittsburgh thursday 
the benefits which would total 288 a week for a claimant with 
two dependents will be paid retroactive to march 2 when the 
strike began the benefits last up to 26 weeks wofford said 
now were ready to stay out for another six months said 
dick erath of pittsburgh who wore a greyhound drivers uniform as 
he marched with hundreds of aflcio members during a downtown 
pittsburgh demonstration 
woffords announcement was met with a standing ovation at the 
convention which has drawn more than 2000 labor leaders to 
pittsburgh 
until now unemployment benefits have been awarded only on an 
individual basis according to greyhound spokeswoman elizabeth 
hale the company plans to appeal the benefits she said 
nobody has been locked out ms hale said the strike was 
called by the union 
under pennsylvania law employees are eligible to collect the 
benefits when their unemployment results from a lockout the 
refusal by an employer to allow employees to come to work 
the state labor department ruled greyhound imposed new contract 
terms on the workers despite an offer by amalgamated transit union 
members to continue working under terms of an expired pact during 
negotiations 
greyhound has hired 2754 replacement drivers to run its buses 
along with 539 union drivers who have crossed picket lines the 
union represents 6300 drivers and 3000 maintenance and office 
workers 
negotiations are scheduled to resume saturday in the offices of 
the federal mediation and conciliation service in washington dc 
the bargaining session would be the first since march 18 when the 
company broke off talks blaming violence associated with the strike 
</TEXT>
